1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:00,880
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,920 --> 00:00:03,360
Failure and Success

3
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:11,440
The older Monsieur Bovary, Monsieur 
Charles Denis Bartholome Bovary,  

4
00:00:11,440 --> 00:00:16,560
had been a good-looking man when younger, 
with a big moustache and rings on his fingers.  

5
00:00:17,840 --> 00:00:23,760
He was not, however, an impressive man, 
and although he wore expensive clothes,  

6
00:00:23,760 --> 00:00:30,320
he always looked like an uncomfortable mixture 
of a military man and a cheap shopkeeper. His  

7
00:00:30,320 --> 00:00:36,400
good looks and ability to sell himself did, 
nevertheless, win him a wife with a good income.  

8
00:00:37,520 --> 00:00:43,840
After he was safely married, he lived for two or 
three years on her money. He ate and drank well,  

9
00:00:44,560 --> 00:00:47,840
and spent his days lying in bed till midday,  

10
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:52,320
smoking his pipe and never coming home 
till the theatres and cafes closed.

11
00:00:54,240 --> 00:00:59,360
When his father-in-law died, the old man 
left very little money to his daughter.  

12
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:07,520
Disappointed, Monsieur Bovary tried to start a 
textile business, but lost a lot of money and  

13
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:13,520
finally retired into the country with the idea 
of showing the people there how to run a farm.  

14
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:21,920
However, he knew as little about agriculture as he 
did about textiles. He rode his horses instead of  

15
00:01:21,920 --> 00:01:28,560
making them work, ate the fattest chickens instead 
of selling them, and cleaned his shooting-boots  

16
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:35,760
with his own best bacon-fat. He soon discovered 
that he had little chance of making a fortune.

17
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:44,080
Around this time he found a place on the 
borders of Caux and Picardy, half farm,  

18
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:50,960
half private house, which he could rent for two 
hundred francs a year. He took it and there,  

19
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:58,240
an angry, disappointed man, at war with the rest 
of the world, he shut himself up at the age of  

20
00:01:58,240 --> 00:02:07,840
forty-five. He said that he was disgusted with 
other people and wanted only to live by himself.

21
00:02:07,840 --> 00:02:11,280
At the beginning, his wife had 
loved him above all others,  

22
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:17,920
but this only seemed to add to his dislike of 
the world and he never had a kind word for her.  

23
00:02:18,880 --> 00:02:24,080
She had been cheerful, kind-hearted 
and friendly, but as she grew older,  

24
00:02:24,080 --> 00:02:30,080
in the same way that good wine turns into 
vinegar, she became bad-tempered and bad company.  

25
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:37,760
She was a hard worker, though, unlike her 
husband. She was always on her feet, always busy,  

26
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:43,920
hurrying to see the lawyers, knowing exactly 
when the next bills had to be paid. Indoors  

27
00:02:43,920 --> 00:02:50,320
she was always working: sewing, washing, keeping 
an eye on the men and paying them their wages.  

28
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:56,240
Her lord and master, paying no attention to what 
was going on around him, sat smoking by the fire.

29
00:02:58,160 --> 00:03:02,640
When the first Madame Bovary had a 
child, it became the centre of her  

30
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:08,400
world. The child's father, however, would 
have been happy to let him go without shoes.  

31
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:13,520
He said that it would be more natural not to 
give him clothes and to let him run around  

32
00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:19,840
like a young animal. In contrast to his wife's 
ideas, he thought a boy would grow up to be a  

33
00:03:19,840 --> 00:03:26,000
better man if he undressed in the cold, learned to 
drink alcohol and laughed at the village priest.  

34
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:32,400
The child, a gentle little thing, made 
little progress in this kind of education.  

35
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:38,720
His mother always kept him close to her; she 
cut out pictures for him from the newspaper  

36
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:46,400
and made up countless stories. In loving her son, 
she was looking for something to make up for the  

37
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:53,600
loneliness of her life. She dreamed he would be 
famous. She could see him as a tall, handsome,  

38
00:03:53,600 --> 00:04:00,480
clever man, high up in the government service. 
She taught him to read, and to sing - while she  

39
00:04:00,480 --> 00:04:07,600
played on her old piano. Monsieur Bovary said this 
was all a waste of time. How were they ever going  

40
00:04:07,600 --> 00:04:15,040
to afford to educate him for a government job, or 
help him start in business? Madame Bovary bit her  

41
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:21,200
lip and did not argue with her husband, and the 
child was allowed to run wild in the village.

42
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:27,920
He went around with the farm workers, scared 
the birds by throwing stones at them, looked  

43
00:04:27,920 --> 00:04:34,240
for wild fruit, helped in the fields, wandered 
through the woods and played with other children.  

44
00:04:35,280 --> 00:04:38,480
On Saints' days, he helped 
ring the bells in the church,  

45
00:04:38,480 --> 00:04:43,600
and he loved to hang on to the big rope and 
feel himself carried up as it rose in the air.  

46
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:49,360
And he grew as strong as a young oak 
tree, with big hands and red cheeks.

47
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:56,000
When he reached the age of twelve, his 
mother managed to arrange for him to begin  

48
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:02,480
his studies with the priest, but the lessons were 
so short and badly organized that they did not do  

49
00:05:02,480 --> 00:05:09,920
him much good. Sometimes it would be hot and the 
child would grow tired, and before long the old  

50
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:16,560
man would be sleeping with his mouth wide open. At 
other times the priest would see Charles playing  

51
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:22,640
with his friends and would call him over to test 
his Latin verbs. But then, perhaps, it would begin  

52
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:29,680
to rain, or someone they knew would come along, 
and lessons would be over for that day. The priest  

53
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:34,640
always had a good word for his pupil, though, and 
said that the young man had a very good memory.

54
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:41,760
By the time young Charles was thirteen, even 
his father saw that something must be done,  

55
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:48,160
and Charles left his unhappy home to spend 
three unhappy years in the College at Rouen.  

56
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:52,480
He wrote to his mother every 
week; he did his homework.  

57
00:05:53,360 --> 00:06:00,080
He never did very well in his studies, but he 
never failed altogether. At the end of three  

58
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:05,840
years, his mother took him away from the College, 
with the plan that he should study medicine.

59
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:12,560
She got him a room on the fourth floor of a house 
overlooking a little river. She made arrangements  

60
00:06:12,560 --> 00:06:18,800
for his meals, found some bits of furniture - a 
table and a couple of chairs and an old bed - and  

61
00:06:18,800 --> 00:06:25,840
made sure there was plenty of firewood to keep 
her poor boy warm. After a week of preparations  

62
00:06:25,840 --> 00:06:34,160
she went back home, asking him over and over 
again to look after himself and to study hard.

63
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:38,800
The list of lectures which he read at the 
beginning of the term made his head spin.  

64
00:06:39,840 --> 00:06:44,480
There were lectures on subjects he had never 
heard of, with names he could not even pronounce.  

65
00:06:45,520 --> 00:06:50,640
He listened as hard as he could, but he could not 
understand what the lecturers were talking about.  

66
00:06:51,840 --> 00:06:56,000
However, he attended every lecture 
and filled notebook after notebook.  

67
00:06:56,800 --> 00:07:01,920
He got through his work like a horse that is 
used to turn a mill-wheel, going round and round  

68
00:07:01,920 --> 00:07:07,920
in the same place with his eyes covered, never 
knowing what he was doing or where he was going.

69
00:07:09,840 --> 00:07:15,040
Charles failed his medical examinations the 
first time - the course was too difficult for  

70
00:07:15,040 --> 00:07:20,720
him. But his mother still believed in him, 
and made his father pay for one more year.  

71
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:26,800
This time Charles managed to pass 
and his mother began to plan again.  

72
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:33,360
First he must have somewhere to 
work, and then he must have a wife.

73
00:07:35,360 --> 00:07:41,440
The first problem was solved when the old 
doctor in Tostes, a small town near Rouen, died.  

74
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:49,760
Charles became the next doctor. Then his 
mother found a 45-year-old widow in Dieppe,  

75
00:07:49,760 --> 00:07:52,320
with an income of twelve hundred francs a year.  

76
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:58,000
Though she was ugly and bad-tempered (and 
twenty-five years older than Charles),  

77
00:07:58,640 --> 00:08:03,680
her income made her attractive and Charles 
thought the marriage would make his life better.  

78
00:08:05,040 --> 00:08:12,720
He thought he would now have freedom and money 
to spend. He was wrong. His wife was in charge.  

79
00:08:13,280 --> 00:08:18,960
She told him what to say, and what not to say. 
She opened his letters, watched his movements  

80
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:23,760
and, when women patients were in the 
surgery, she listened from the next room.  

81
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:31,520
At night, when Charles came to bed, she put her 
long bony arms round his neck and told him all her  

82
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:39,120
troubles. He did not love her, he loved someone 
else. Yes, she knew she would always be unhappy.  

83
00:08:39,760 --> 00:08:45,120
And she always ended by asking him for some 
medicine - and for a little more love.
 
 
 

84
00:08:48,480 --> 00:08:49,200
CHAPTER TWO

85
00:08:50,640 --> 00:08:54,320
Mademoiselle Emma

86
00:08:54,320 --> 00:09:00,800
One night, Charles received a letter asking him 
to come at once to a farm at Les Bertaux where the  

87
00:09:00,800 --> 00:09:07,840
farmer had broken his leg. The night was dark 
and the farm was twenty-five kilometres away,  

88
00:09:07,840 --> 00:09:14,080
but the farmer was a rich man and Charles was 
still building up his business. So at four o'clock  

89
00:09:14,080 --> 00:09:22,240
in the morning, Dr Bovary set out. A child was 
waiting at an open gate as he approached the farm.

90
00:09:22,240 --> 00:09:24,240
'Are you the doctor?' he asked.

91
00:09:25,920 --> 00:09:30,320
As Charles rode along, he learned from 
the boy that Monsieur Rouault had broken  

92
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:36,720
his leg the night before. He also learned 
that he had lost his wife two years ago,  

93
00:09:36,720 --> 00:09:41,360
and had no one with him now except for his 
daughter, who looked after the house for him.

94
00:09:42,640 --> 00:09:47,760
Mademoiselle Emma, the farmer's daughter, came 
to the door and showed him into the kitchen.  

95
00:09:48,800 --> 00:09:53,600
A fire was burning and the men's dinner 
was cooking in big polished pans.  

96
00:09:54,560 --> 00:09:59,920
Charles went upstairs to see the farmer. 
The broken leg was a simple problem  

97
00:09:59,920 --> 00:10:03,840
and Charles asked the servant and the 
young woman to help with the patient.  

98
00:10:05,120 --> 00:10:10,400
As they tied up the farmer's leg, Charles was 
surprised to see how white her nails were.  

99
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:17,520
Her hands, however, were not beautiful 
- perhaps a little too red. She herself  

100
00:10:17,520 --> 00:10:24,240
was too tall, and she did not have the kind 
of soft figure Charles liked. Her good point  

101
00:10:24,240 --> 00:10:31,840
was her eyes. They were dark, almost black, 
and she looked at you honestly and fearlessly.

102
00:10:34,320 --> 00:10:38,560
As soon as he had finished looking after 
his patient, the doctor was invited by  

103
00:10:38,560 --> 00:10:45,440
Monsieur Rouault to eat before he left. Charles 
went down into the room below, where two places  

104
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:51,520
had been laid with shining silver on a small 
table and Mademoiselle Emma was waiting for him.  

105
00:10:52,880 --> 00:10:56,720
A smell of flowers and clean 
clothes came from a cupboard  

106
00:10:56,720 --> 00:11:02,080
opposite the window and on the floor, in 
the corner, stood a few bags of wheat.  

107
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:06,720
Someone had hung a drawing of a Greek 
god in the middle of one of the walls.  

108
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:13,840
It was in an attractive frame, and written at 
the bottom were the words 'To my dear Father'.

109
00:11:15,840 --> 00:11:20,080
They began by talking about Monsieur 
Rouault, and went on to discuss the  

110
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:26,080
weather and the cold winter. Mademoiselle 
Emma did not like the country very much,  

111
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:31,760
especially now she had almost all the 
responsibility of the farm on her shoulders.

112
00:11:33,680 --> 00:11:38,560
When Charles, who had been upstairs to say goodbye 
to the farmer, came back into the dining room,  

113
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:44,400
he found her standing by the window looking 
out into the garden. She turned round.

114
00:11:46,480 --> 00:11:49,040
'Are you looking for something?' she asked.

115
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:53,840
'Yes, I'm trying to find my 
riding-whip,' he replied,  

116
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:57,680
and he began to look behind 
the doors and under the chairs.

117
00:11:59,360 --> 00:12:05,520
Mademoiselle Emma found it between the bags of 
wheat and the wall, and Charles went over to help.  

118
00:12:06,880 --> 00:12:13,760
As he bent down, he felt the young woman's 
back rubbing against his chest. She stood up,  

119
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:18,320
blushing, and, looking at him over 
her shoulder, handed him his whip.

120
00:12:20,720 --> 00:12:26,480
Instead of going back to Les Bertaux three days 
later, as he said he would, he returned the next  

121
00:12:26,480 --> 00:12:34,960
day, and he then went to the farm twice a week. 
After forty-six days, Monsieur Rouault could move  

122
00:12:34,960 --> 00:12:40,320
around without help, and people began to say 
what an excellent doctor Monsieur Bovary was.  

123
00:12:41,520 --> 00:12:47,600
Pere Rouault said the very best doctors in Yvetot 
or Rouen itself could not have treated him better.

124
00:12:49,440 --> 00:12:53,040
Charles did not ask himself why 
he liked going to Les Bertaux.  

125
00:12:54,240 --> 00:12:58,720
If he had thought about it he would have 
said to himself that it was a serious case,  

126
00:12:58,720 --> 00:13:05,440
or he expected to earn a good fee. But was that 
really the reason why these visits to the farm  

127
00:13:05,440 --> 00:13:12,240
were so pleasant? On days when he was visiting, 
he got up early and rode to the farm as quickly  

128
00:13:12,240 --> 00:13:18,160
as he could, only stopping to clean his boots and 
to put on his black gloves before going into the  

129
00:13:18,160 --> 00:13:24,640
house. He liked to ride into the yard, and see 
the farm boys as they came forward to meet him.  

130
00:13:25,360 --> 00:13:31,360
He liked the house, and Monsieur Rouault, who 
held his hand and said he had saved his life;  

131
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:37,200
he liked the sound of Mademoiselle Emma's wooden 
shoes on the clean stone floor of the kitchen.

132
00:13:39,440 --> 00:13:43,200
When he left, she always came 
with him to the top of the steps,  

133
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:45,680
and would wait with him until 
the boys brought his horse.  

134
00:13:47,440 --> 00:13:51,760
One day, at the end of the winter, it 
started to rain as he was leaving the house.  

135
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:59,920
She went back inside for an umbrella and put it 
up. It was a silk one, and it caught the sunlight,  

136
00:13:59,920 --> 00:14:04,160
reflecting little coloured patches of 
light on to the whiteness of her skin.  

137
00:14:05,680 --> 00:14:10,240
She smiled at him, and you could hear 
the sound of the rain drops as they fell,  

138
00:14:10,240 --> 00:14:13,600
one by one, on to the tight surface of the silk.

139
00:14:15,680 --> 00:14:21,360
When Charles first began his visits to Les 
Bertaux, his wife always asked about his patient.  

140
00:14:22,560 --> 00:14:27,040
But when she learned that the farmer's daughter 
had been to school and had learned dancing,  

141
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:34,080
geography and drawing, and could play the piano, 
her interest changed to anger and dislike.  

142
00:14:35,360 --> 00:14:40,880
At first she made unfriendly remarks about 
Mademoiselle Rouault, but Charles ignored them  

143
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:47,840
because he did not want an argument. So at last 
she told him to his face what she thought of him,  

144
00:14:47,840 --> 00:14:52,960
and he did not know what to reply. 
Why did he keep going to Les Bertaux?  

145
00:14:52,960 --> 00:14:56,400
Monsieur Rouault was well again 
now and he had not paid his bill.  

146
00:14:56,960 --> 00:15:02,960
Ah, she knew all about it! There was someone 
else there, someone who was a good talker,  

147
00:15:02,960 --> 00:15:09,040
someone who was well educated and clever. 
That was what he liked - young, pretty ladies!

148
00:15:10,560 --> 00:15:15,760
So Charles agreed to stop his visits to 
Les Bertaux, but now that he could not see  

149
00:15:15,760 --> 00:15:24,160
Mademoiselle Emma he decided he could love her. 
His wife was so unattractive, just skin and bone.  

150
00:15:24,160 --> 00:15:30,000
She wore the same black clothes and gray 
stockings, the same ugly shoes all year round.  

151
00:15:30,880 --> 00:15:36,160
So if he could not see the farmer's 
daughter any more, he would dream of her!

152
00:15:37,920 --> 00:15:45,200
This unhappy situation lasted for several 
months until, one fine day in the early spring,  

153
00:15:45,200 --> 00:15:50,960
the lawyer who had looked after Madame Bovary's 
affairs left town with all his clients' money.  

154
00:15:52,160 --> 00:15:56,320
She still had a share in a ship 
that was worth six thousand francs,  

155
00:15:56,320 --> 00:16:01,840
and her house in Dieppe, but there was nothing 
left of that fortune she had been so proud of.

156
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:06,480
And when her financial affairs 
were looked into more carefully,  

157
00:16:07,040 --> 00:16:14,080
Charles's father found out that the house in 
Dieppe was mortgaged and her share in the vessel  

158
00:16:14,080 --> 00:16:22,480
was not worth more than two hundred francs. She 
had lied, the good lady! Monsieur Bovary senior  

159
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:26,880
was so angry that he took up a chair 
and smashed it on the stone floor,  

160
00:16:26,880 --> 00:16:32,240
and he told his wife she had ruined her son 
by making him marry an old woman like that.  

161
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:37,440
They came to Tostes to tell Charles's 
rich wife what they thought of her.  

162
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:43,760
There was a terrible argument. Heloise begged 
her husband to defend her against his parents,  

163
00:16:44,320 --> 00:16:49,840
and Charles did his best, but the old people 
were still angry when they left the house.

164
00:16:50,800 --> 00:16:57,360
The damage had been done. A week later, as 
she was hanging out the washing in the yard,  

165
00:16:57,360 --> 00:17:03,920
Heloise Bovary found that she was spitting blood. 
The next day, while Charles had his back to her,  

166
00:17:03,920 --> 00:17:13,200
opening the curtains, she cried out, 'Oh God!' 
and fell to the floor. She was dead! How amazing!

167
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,920
When the funeral was over, 
Charles returned to the house.  

168
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:26,240
He went up into the bedroom and saw her 
dress hanging up at the foot of the bed. He  

169
00:17:26,240 --> 00:17:34,880
stayed there until it was dark, lost in sorrowful 
thought. After all, perhaps she had loved him.
 
 
 

170
00:17:38,480 --> 00:17:39,280
CHAPTER THREE

171
00:17:40,320 --> 00:17:41,360
A New Wife

172
00:17:43,680 --> 00:17:49,360
One morning Pere Rouault came to pay Charles 
for his treatment, and to say how sorry he was  

173
00:17:49,360 --> 00:17:56,960
to hear about his wife's death. Seeing how unhappy 
Charles looked, he said, 'You must make an effort,  

174
00:17:56,960 --> 00:18:05,280
Monsieur Bovary; you will be happy again one day. 
Come and see us. My daughter asks about you and  

175
00:18:05,280 --> 00:18:11,600
says that you are forgetting her. Spring will 
soon be here. Come and shoot a rabbit or two!'

176
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:17,360
Charles took his advice. He 
went back to Les Bertaux,  

177
00:18:17,360 --> 00:18:23,360
and found everything there just the same as 
before. The apple trees were already in flower,  

178
00:18:23,920 --> 00:18:29,760
and Pere Rouault did his best to make the doctor 
feel comfortable. He even told him a few stories,  

179
00:18:30,320 --> 00:18:35,600
and Charles was surprised to find himself 
laughing. When he remembered his wife  

180
00:18:35,600 --> 00:18:42,320
he became serious again, but then the coffee 
came in and he thought no more about her.

181
00:18:42,320 --> 00:18:46,880
Back home, he also thought of her less 
and less as he got used to living alone.  

182
00:18:47,760 --> 00:18:50,800
He was free now to have his meals when he liked,  

183
00:18:50,800 --> 00:18:56,480
he could go out and come in without having to 
give explanations, and when he was very tired  

184
00:18:56,480 --> 00:19:02,720
he could stretch out his arms and legs in bed as 
far as he liked. He gave himself little treats,  

185
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:10,880
let himself feel self-pity and let people be 
nice to him. Moreover, his wife's death had been  

186
00:19:10,880 --> 00:19:16,240
rather good for him professionally because, 
for a whole month, people had been saying,  

187
00:19:17,120 --> 00:19:23,840
'Poor young man! What bad luck!' So his name 
had been heard and his practice had increased  

188
00:19:24,640 --> 00:19:32,720
and he could go to Les Bertaux whenever he wanted 
to. He was strangely happy and, looking at himself  

189
00:19:32,720 --> 00:19:37,840
in the mirror as he brushed his moustache, 
he thought he had become better-looking.

190
00:19:39,360 --> 00:19:44,080
He arrived at the farm one day at about three 
o'clock when everyone was out in the fields.  

191
00:19:44,880 --> 00:19:52,080
He went into the kitchen, but did not see Emma at 
first. The sunlight shone on the kitchen floor in  

192
00:19:52,080 --> 00:19:58,960
long narrow bars, reflecting on the ceiling. Flies 
on the table crawled up the glasses that had not  

193
00:19:58,960 --> 00:20:05,840
been washed, or drowned in the cider in the bottom 
of a jug. Between the window and the fireplace  

194
00:20:05,840 --> 00:20:13,280
Emma sat sewing. She had no scarf around her neck, 
and he could see the fine hairs on her shoulders.

195
00:20:15,440 --> 00:20:23,280
Like all country people, she offered him a drink. 
He said no at first, but at last, with a laugh,  

196
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:28,880
she persuaded him to have a glass with her. She 
went to the cupboard and brought out the bottle,  

197
00:20:29,520 --> 00:20:36,640
took down two small glasses, filled one, poured 
two or three drops into the other and, tapping it  

198
00:20:36,640 --> 00:20:44,240
against the doctor's, put it to her lips. As it 
was nearly empty, she leaned back to drink and,  

199
00:20:44,240 --> 00:20:51,200
with her head back, she began to laugh because 
she could not taste anything. At the same time,  

200
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:55,760
she tried to catch some of the drops from the 
bottom of the glass with the tip of her tongue.

201
00:20:58,240 --> 00:21:03,440
Then she sat down and took up her work again 
- a white cotton sock which she was repairing.  

202
00:21:04,800 --> 00:21:11,680
She worked with her head bent forward. She did 
not talk, nor did Charles. As he watched her,  

203
00:21:11,680 --> 00:21:17,200
the only sound he could hear was the excitement 
of a hen that had laid an egg in the yard outside.

204
00:21:19,520 --> 00:21:26,240
After some time, Emma started to talk to him. 
She had been complaining ever since the spring  

205
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:31,680
about feeling dizzy; she wondered whether 
bathing in the sea would do her any good.  

206
00:21:32,960 --> 00:21:37,440
She began to talk about her convent 
school, and Charles about his college days.  

207
00:21:38,640 --> 00:21:43,920
They went upstairs to her room, where she showed 
him her old music books and the prizes she had  

208
00:21:43,920 --> 00:21:49,360
won. And she went on to speak of her mother, 
and even pointed out the bed in the garden  

209
00:21:49,360 --> 00:21:54,720
where she gathered flowers on the first Friday 
in every month, to lay on her mothers grave.  

210
00:21:56,240 --> 00:22:00,800
She said she would like to live in town in 
the winter, although perhaps the long days  

211
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:05,840
made the country even more boring in the 
summer; and according to what she was saying,  

212
00:22:05,840 --> 00:22:12,320
her voice was clear and strong, musical or almost 
a whisper, as if she were speaking to herself.

213
00:22:15,520 --> 00:22:21,120
That night, as he was riding home, Charles 
thought about the different things she had said,  

214
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,880
trying to remember them exactly 
to discover what they meant,  

215
00:22:25,680 --> 00:22:29,760
so that he might understand how her 
life had been before he met her.  

216
00:22:31,200 --> 00:22:37,200
Then he began to wonder how she would become 
if she married - and whom she would marry.  

217
00:22:38,880 --> 00:22:46,240
Unfortunately, old Rouault was apparently 
very wealthy, and she herself... so beautiful!  

218
00:22:47,440 --> 00:22:54,320
But the thought kept coming to him: 'The doctor 
wants a wife. Yes, the doctor wants a wife.'

219
00:22:56,400 --> 00:23:03,440
That night he could not sleep. He got up, took a 
drink from the water-jug and opened his window.  

220
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:11,520
The sky was filled with stars, a warm 
breeze was blowing and, a long way off,  

221
00:23:11,520 --> 00:23:18,720
some dogs were barking. He turned his head 
towards Les Bertaux. Thinking that, after all,  

222
00:23:18,720 --> 00:23:25,840
he had nothing to lose by it, Charles made up his 
mind to ask her to marry him. But every time he  

223
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:31,840
was alone with her, the fear of being unable to 
find the right words left him unable to speak.

224
00:23:33,360 --> 00:23:37,520
In fact Pere Rouault would have been 
happy to see his daughter married,  

225
00:23:37,520 --> 00:23:43,840
especially as she was very little use in the 
house. He made excuses for her, telling himself  

226
00:23:43,840 --> 00:23:49,680
that she had too much intelligence for the farming 
life. When, therefore, he noticed that Charles  

227
00:23:49,680 --> 00:23:54,960
blushed each time he was near his daughter, and 
that the young man was clearly interested in her,  

228
00:23:55,520 --> 00:24:00,720
he gave the matter some thought. Although 
Charles was not the sort of man he would have  

229
00:24:00,720 --> 00:24:06,640
chosen for a son-in-law, he was well educated 
and a hard worker, and would not ask him for  

230
00:24:06,640 --> 00:24:12,800
too much money to take his daughter off his 
hands. This mattered, as Monsieur Rouault had  

231
00:24:12,800 --> 00:24:17,840
debts with most of his suppliers and had 
just had to sell a large amount of land.

232
00:24:18,960 --> 00:24:23,280
'If he asks me,' he said to 
himself, 'he can have her.'

233
00:24:25,680 --> 00:24:32,800
A little later, Charles came to spend three 
days at Les Bertaux. The time went quickly,  

234
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:35,360
and he never seemed to find 
the right moment to speak.  

235
00:24:36,720 --> 00:24:40,720
As he was leaving, Monsieur Rouault 
came out to see him on his way.  

236
00:24:41,600 --> 00:24:47,600
They had reached a bend in the road and were 
preparing to say goodbye. It was now or never.  

237
00:24:48,640 --> 00:24:53,280
Charles gave himself until the corner of the 
field and at last, when they had passed it,  

238
00:24:53,280 --> 00:24:59,840
he said, almost in a whisper, 'Monsieur Rouault, 
there is something I want to say to you.'

239
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:03,920
They stopped. Charles could not speak.

240
00:25:06,080 --> 00:25:11,120
'Come on then, out with it! Do you 
think I don't know what it's all about?'  

241
00:25:11,680 --> 00:25:13,840
said the farmer, laughing quietly.

242
00:25:13,840 --> 00:25:20,080
'Pere Rouault... Pere Rouault...'

243
00:25:20,080 --> 00:25:21,840
'Well,' the farmer went on,  

244
00:25:23,120 --> 00:25:29,280
'there's nothing I would like better. But, 
though I am sure my little girl will agree,  

245
00:25:29,920 --> 00:25:37,200
we must put the question to her. You go on; I'll 
go back to the farm. If it's yes, there'll be no  

246
00:25:37,200 --> 00:25:43,840
need for you to come back... She'll need some time 
to get used to the idea! But so you can be sure,  

247
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:49,200
I'll open the window in the front bedroom. 
You'll be able to see it from the back here.'

248
00:25:50,720 --> 00:25:53,200
And with these words he returned to the house.

249
00:25:55,200 --> 00:26:01,760
Charles tied his horse to a tree. He hurried 
back to take up his position, and waited.  

250
00:26:03,200 --> 00:26:10,960
Half an hour went by, then nineteen more 
minutes, which he timed by his watch. Suddenly  

251
00:26:10,960 --> 00:26:16,880
something banged against the wall. The 
window was open. She had accepted him!

252
00:26:19,200 --> 00:26:22,160
Next day, by nine o'clock, he was at the farm.  

253
00:26:23,360 --> 00:26:26,880
Emma blushed when he came in, 
but tried to laugh a little, too.  

254
00:26:28,240 --> 00:26:34,880
Pere Rouault took his son-in-law in his arms. Then 
they began to talk about the arrangements. They  

255
00:26:34,880 --> 00:26:40,160
had plenty of time before them, since the wedding 
could not take place until at least twelve months  

256
00:26:40,160 --> 00:26:45,200
after the death of Charles's first wife, and 
that meant the spring of the following year.

257
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:54,640
The wedding dinner was a grand affair. Forty-three 
people sat down at the table and remained there  

258
00:26:54,640 --> 00:27:02,000
for sixteen hours, and the party which followed 
went on for several days. For most of the guests  

259
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:08,080
it was a wedding to remember. The only 
person who did not enter the spirit of things  

260
00:27:08,080 --> 00:27:14,240
seemed to be Madame Bovary senior, who sat through 
the whole event with a sour look on her face.  

261
00:27:15,760 --> 00:27:22,720
No one had asked her about the bride's dress, or 
the arrangements for the party. She went to bed  

262
00:27:22,720 --> 00:27:29,920
early. Her husband, however, did not follow 
her, but sent into Saint-Victor for cigars.  

263
00:27:30,880 --> 00:27:36,480
He sat with the men and smoked until the morning, 
drinking and laughing until the sun rose.

264
00:27:38,480 --> 00:27:44,880
On the day of the wedding, Charles had not been a 
great success; he was neither a confident speaker  

265
00:27:44,880 --> 00:27:53,200
nor a great teller of jokes. Next day, however, 
he seemed a different man. While Emma did not  

266
00:27:53,200 --> 00:28:00,240
give the smallest idea of what she thought about 
it all, Charles was completely changed. He called  

267
00:28:00,240 --> 00:28:07,040
her his wife, his dear, kept asking where she 
was, looked for her everywhere and frequently  

268
00:28:07,040 --> 00:28:12,240
took her out into the yard, where he was seen 
among the trees with his arm round her waist.

269
00:28:14,240 --> 00:28:18,000
Two days after the wedding, 
the newly married couple left.  

270
00:28:19,200 --> 00:28:21,840
Charles could not be away 
from his practice any longer.  

271
00:28:22,560 --> 00:28:28,080
Monsieur Rouault sent them home in his carriage, 
and went with them himself as far as Vassonville.  

272
00:28:29,280 --> 00:28:36,320
There he kissed his daughter goodbye, and started 
for home again on foot. When he had gone about  

273
00:28:36,320 --> 00:28:41,040
a hundred metres he stopped and looked back 
at the carriage disappearing down the road.  

274
00:28:42,400 --> 00:28:47,680
Then he thought of his own wedding. Like 
Charles, he, too, had been happy when he  

275
00:28:47,680 --> 00:28:54,240
took his wife from her father's house, back to his 
own. She had ridden behind him through the snow;  

276
00:28:54,240 --> 00:29:01,040
it was near Christmas and the country all white. 
One of her arms held on to him, and over the other  

277
00:29:01,040 --> 00:29:08,080
she carried her basket. When he turned his head 
he saw close by him, just above his shoulder, her  

278
00:29:08,080 --> 00:29:15,520
little smiling face. To warm her fingers she had 
pushed them, from time to time, inside his jacket.  

279
00:29:17,360 --> 00:29:21,600
How far away it seemed now. He looked back again,  

280
00:29:22,400 --> 00:29:28,480
and there was nothing to be seen along the 
road. He felt as sad as an empty house.

281
00:29:31,920 --> 00:29:35,840
Monsieur and Madame Charles arrived 
at Tostes at about six o'clock.  

282
00:29:36,800 --> 00:29:40,480
The neighbours came to their windows to 
take a look at the doctor's new wife.  

283
00:29:41,520 --> 00:29:46,400
The old servant came to meet them and made 
excuses for the dinner not being ready,  

284
00:29:46,400 --> 00:29:53,840
and suggested that, for the moment, Madame 
should come in and look around the house.
 
 
 

285
00:29:54,640 --> 00:29:55,440
CHAPTER FOUR

286
00:29:56,320 --> 00:29:57,280
Two Worlds

287
00:29:59,440 --> 00:30:04,480
The front of the house looked straight on to 
the street. Hanging up behind the front door  

288
00:30:04,480 --> 00:30:10,880
were the doctor's coat, a belt, a black leather 
cap and, on the floor in the corner, a pair of  

289
00:30:10,880 --> 00:30:17,280
boots covered with dried mud. To the right was 
the sitting room, where meals were also eaten.  

290
00:30:19,360 --> 00:30:23,520
White cotton curtains with a red 
border were hung along the windows,  

291
00:30:23,520 --> 00:30:30,080
and above the fireplace there was a splendid clock 
and a head of Hippocrates. On the other side of  

292
00:30:30,080 --> 00:30:36,320
the passage was Charles's consulting room, a 
little box of a place about two metres wide  

293
00:30:36,320 --> 00:30:42,000
with a table, three ordinary chairs 
and one armchair. A set of books,  

294
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:46,640
the Dictionary of Medical Science, took up 
almost all the six shelves of the bookcase;  

295
00:30:47,200 --> 00:30:53,920
they had been owned by many earlier doctors in 
Tostes, but never read. The smell of cooking  

296
00:30:53,920 --> 00:30:58,720
would come in through the thin wall during 
consultations, and anyone in the kitchen could  

297
00:30:58,720 --> 00:31:03,840
hear the patients coughing and talking to the 
doctor as clearly as if they were in the room.

298
00:31:05,920 --> 00:31:08,960
The long, narrow garden ran down to the fields.  

299
00:31:09,920 --> 00:31:16,320
Fruit trees grew along the stone walls and four 
flower beds, planted with weak-looking roses,  

300
00:31:16,320 --> 00:31:22,000
were set around a square area which was 
used for vegetables. At the far end,  

301
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:27,360
under some low trees, there was a small white 
statue of a priest reading a prayer book.

302
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:36,080
Emma went up to see the bedrooms. There was 
no furniture in the first one but the second,  

303
00:31:36,080 --> 00:31:43,840
their bedroom, contained their new bed with its 
red curtains. There was a box made of seashells on  

304
00:31:43,840 --> 00:31:51,200
a chest of drawers and on the desk, by the window, 
stood a glass bottle with a bunch of dried flowers  

305
00:31:51,200 --> 00:31:56,480
tied with white ribbon. They were the 
flowers from his first wife's wedding.  

306
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:04,160
Charles saw her looking at them, and took them 
out of the room. Sitting in an armchair, while her  

307
00:32:04,160 --> 00:32:10,000
maid unpacked her things, Emma thought about her 
own wedding flowers, lying in one of the boxes,  

308
00:32:10,880 --> 00:32:13,840
and she wondered what would 
happen to them if she died young.

309
00:32:16,960 --> 00:32:23,360
Charles was a happy man now. In bed in the 
morning, with her head on the pillow beside him,  

310
00:32:23,360 --> 00:32:27,840
he would look at the sunlight on her cheek 
and at her beautiful eyes when she woke.  

311
00:32:28,640 --> 00:32:34,640
He could lose himself in those eyes, looking 
into them until he saw a tiny picture of himself,  

312
00:32:34,640 --> 00:32:41,520
his nightcap on his head and the collar of his 
shirt open. As soon as he was up and dressed, she  

313
00:32:41,520 --> 00:32:47,520
would go to the window to see him start his day. 
Down in the street below, Charles would prepare to  

314
00:32:47,520 --> 00:32:54,160
get on to his horse while she went on talking to 
him from above. Sometimes she might find a feather  

315
00:32:54,160 --> 00:32:59,520
and send it floating through the air to be caught 
in the long hair on his old white horse's neck.  

316
00:33:00,400 --> 00:33:05,120
As he rode off, Charles would blow her 
a kiss and she would wave back to him.

317
00:33:07,120 --> 00:33:10,800
It was the first time in his life 
that he had tasted such happiness.  

318
00:33:11,760 --> 00:33:15,920
He had been lonely and friendless at 
school and when he was studying medicine.  

319
00:33:16,800 --> 00:33:20,800
And then he had had fourteen months 
of married life with the widow,  

320
00:33:20,800 --> 00:33:27,840
whose feet, in bed, were like lumps of ice. 
But now this lovely woman was his for life!

321
00:33:29,920 --> 00:33:35,840
Before she married, Emma too had thought she was 
in love, but the happiness that should have come  

322
00:33:35,840 --> 00:33:43,600
from love was somehow missing. It seemed to 
her that she must have made a mistake, must  

323
00:33:43,600 --> 00:33:49,840
have misunderstood things in one way or another. 
And as she stood by her bedroom window, morning  

324
00:33:49,840 --> 00:33:57,040
after morning, Emma tried hard to understand 
what, exactly, the words joy, love, desire  

325
00:33:57,680 --> 00:34:05,840
meant. They had always seemed so beautiful to her 
in books, but what did they mean in real life?

326
00:34:06,800 --> 00:34:10,560
Novels had always seemed more real 
to her than the life she had to live.  

327
00:34:11,840 --> 00:34:16,560
When she was at her convent school, a teacher 
sometimes secretly lent such books to the  

328
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:23,520
older girls. They were all about love, lovers, 
beautiful girls, ladies in danger, horses ridden  

329
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:30,080
till they dropped dead, dark forests, tears 
and kisses, and gentlemen as brave as lions.  

330
00:34:31,280 --> 00:34:36,880
When she was fifteen, Emma read the works of 
Walter Scott for the first time and found she  

331
00:34:36,880 --> 00:34:43,920
was happier in this imagined past than her rather 
boring present; the characters she read about in  

332
00:34:43,920 --> 00:34:49,280
these books were much more interesting than 
the teachers and students she saw around her.

333
00:34:50,480 --> 00:34:55,600
She had felt a thrill each time she blew back 
the thin paper which protected the pictures.  

334
00:34:56,480 --> 00:35:03,120
She saw young men holding young women in white 
dresses in their arms, or English ladies with  

335
00:35:03,120 --> 00:35:09,920
golden hair, who looked at you with big, bright 
eyes. In her reading she was able to listen to the  

336
00:35:09,920 --> 00:35:17,600
sound of heavenly music and of falling leaves. 
Later, after her mother died, she even fell in  

337
00:35:17,600 --> 00:35:22,880
love with the church and thought of staying in 
the convent, of never going out into the world.  

338
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:28,160
But in her last year of school, she 
began to lose her interest in religion.  

339
00:35:29,200 --> 00:35:33,120
When her father took her away, her 
teachers were not sorry to see her go.  

340
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:38,000
She had, they thought, stopped showing 
any respect for their community.

341
00:35:40,320 --> 00:35:45,280
On her return home, Emma tried to find an 
interest in managing her father's house,  

342
00:35:45,920 --> 00:35:50,320
but she soon grew tired of the country 
and wished herself back in her convent.  

343
00:35:51,760 --> 00:35:55,440
When Charles came to Les 
Bertaux for the first time,  

344
00:35:55,440 --> 00:36:01,440
she thought of herself as a disappointed woman, 
one for whom life had nothing new to offer,  

345
00:36:01,440 --> 00:36:09,040
either in knowledge or experience. Maybe her wish 
for a change - possibly, too, the unrest caused by  

346
00:36:09,040 --> 00:36:14,640
the presence of an unknown man - had been enough 
to make her believe that she was at last in love.  

347
00:36:15,840 --> 00:36:22,000
But now she could not believe that her present 
state was the happiness she had dreamed about.

348
00:36:25,520 --> 00:36:30,400
Nevertheless, she sometimes thought that these 
were, in fact, the happiest days of her life.  

349
00:36:31,600 --> 00:36:36,560
Of course, it would have been so much better if 
they could have gone far away to lands whose names  

350
00:36:36,560 --> 00:36:42,880
fall like music on the ear, where the weddings of 
lovers are followed by mornings of soft delight  

351
00:36:42,880 --> 00:36:49,120
and where, when the sun goes down, you breathe, 
sitting beside the sea, the sweet perfume of  

352
00:36:49,120 --> 00:36:55,920
the lemon trees. Why did her bedroom window not 
look out on to the Swiss or Scottish mountains?  

353
00:36:56,800 --> 00:37:01,280
Why did her husband not stand 
beside her in a black silk jacket,  

354
00:37:01,280 --> 00:37:05,520
the wind blowing his long hair 
back from his pale, white forehead?

355
00:37:07,120 --> 00:37:13,440
But Charles could not read these thoughts, and 
was not able to share her dreams, and as their  

356
00:37:13,440 --> 00:37:19,600
lives became closer Emma, in fact, began to have 
a secret feeling of distance from her husband.  

357
00:37:20,960 --> 00:37:27,200
Charles's conversation was uninteresting to her. 
He told her that when he lived in Rouen he never  

358
00:37:27,200 --> 00:37:34,080
had the smallest desire to go to the theatre. He 
could not swim, he had no idea of how to use a  

359
00:37:34,080 --> 00:37:41,760
sword, he could not fire a gun. He knew nothing, 
and he wanted nothing. He thought she was happy,  

360
00:37:42,320 --> 00:37:46,560
and his heavy, comfortable 
happiness had begun to annoy her.

361
00:37:48,880 --> 00:37:54,400
A few weeks after they came to Tostes, one of 
Charles's patients presented Madame with a little  

362
00:37:54,400 --> 00:38:00,560
Italian hunting dog. She took it with her for 
walks, because she used to go out sometimes just  

363
00:38:00,560 --> 00:38:05,840
to get a few moments to herself and to enjoy 
a change from the garden and the dusty road.

364
00:38:07,200 --> 00:38:12,640
She would go as far as the woods near Banneville, 
along by the empty summer house at the end of the  

365
00:38:12,640 --> 00:38:20,400
wall, towards the open country. There, at the side 
of the lake, the plants grew higher than a man and  

366
00:38:20,400 --> 00:38:27,280
had leaves as sharp as knives. Sitting at the edge 
of the wood among the pink and blue wild flowers,  

367
00:38:27,280 --> 00:38:31,920
her thoughts would wander here and there, 
like her dog, which ran from one place to the  

368
00:38:31,920 --> 00:38:37,840
next chasing the birds and insects. But in the 
same way that her dog always came back to her,  

369
00:38:38,480 --> 00:38:45,840
she always came back to the same 
question: 'My God, why did I marry him?'

370
00:38:47,360 --> 00:38:54,000
She would then call Djali (the name she had given 
her dog) to come to her and, stroking her long,  

371
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:00,480
graceful head, would say, 'Come, kiss your 
mistress; you have no worries, have you?'

372
00:39:02,400 --> 00:39:05,440
Then she would look into the 
creature's beautiful, sad eyes,  

373
00:39:06,080 --> 00:39:08,400
and a feeling of tenderness would come over her.  

374
00:39:09,600 --> 00:39:15,440
Pretending the animal was herself, she would talk 
to her aloud as if she were comforting someone.

375
00:39:17,200 --> 00:39:22,000
Towards the end of September, however, an 
extraordinary event happened in her life:  

376
00:39:22,560 --> 00:39:29,840
she was invited to La Vaubyessard, the home of 
the Marquis d'Andervilliers. The Marquis, who  

377
00:39:29,840 --> 00:39:35,360
had been a Minister in the national government, 
wanted to get back into politics, and he was now  

378
00:39:35,360 --> 00:39:41,760
doing his best to make himself popular. During the 
winter months he had given firewood to the poor,  

379
00:39:41,760 --> 00:39:47,680
and he was always the first to demand new roads 
for his district. During the summer, he had had  

380
00:39:47,680 --> 00:39:53,200
a painful mouth infection, which Charles had 
managed to cure before it became really serious.  

381
00:39:54,240 --> 00:39:59,520
The servant who was sent to Tostes to pay for 
the treatment told his master, when he got back,  

382
00:39:59,520 --> 00:40:04,960
that he had seen some splendid cherries in 
the doctor's little garden. Cherries did not  

383
00:40:04,960 --> 00:40:11,040
grow well at La Vaubyessard, and the Marquis 
asked Bovary to let him have a few baskets.  

384
00:40:12,240 --> 00:40:18,240
He then decided to come in person to thank 
the doctor, saw Emma, and noted that she  

385
00:40:18,240 --> 00:40:23,920
had a pretty figure and good manners. After 
this, the Marquis decided that he would not  

386
00:40:23,920 --> 00:40:29,200
harm his chances in the coming vote if he sent 
the young people an invitation to his house.

387
00:40:30,080 --> 00:40:36,720
And so, one Wednesday at three o'clock, Monsieur 
and Madame Bovary set off in their carriage to  

388
00:40:36,720 --> 00:40:44,800
La Vaubyessard, with a big travelling bag tied on 
behind, and a hatbox fixed in front. They arrived  

389
00:40:44,800 --> 00:40:49,600
when it was getting dark, just as the lamps were 
being lit in the park to guide the carriages.  

390
00:40:50,800 --> 00:40:56,960
The Chateau la Vaubyessard, a large building in 
sixteenth-century style, stood in the centre of  

391
00:40:56,960 --> 00:41:04,000
parkland. A stream flowed between tall trees 
and beneath a bridge, and through the evening  

392
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:09,520
mist they could see cottages and farm buildings. 
Charles stopped the carriage at the foot of the  

393
00:41:09,520 --> 00:41:15,600
steps leading up to the front door, and two 
servants came down to take their bags. Then  

394
00:41:15,600 --> 00:41:21,440
the Marquis came forward and, offering his arm to 
the doctor's lady, walked with her into the hall.

395
00:41:23,120 --> 00:41:30,080
Under the high ceiling, their voices and footsteps 
sounded as if they were in a church. As she passed  

396
00:41:30,080 --> 00:41:35,600
through on her way to the main room, Emma saw 
large, dark paintings of the Marquis's relatives,  

397
00:41:36,160 --> 00:41:41,360
some in the clothes of the royal court, others 
in the uniforms of army or navy officers.  

398
00:41:42,640 --> 00:41:46,800
When the Marquis opened the door 
for them, one of the ladies rose  

399
00:41:46,800 --> 00:41:53,120
(it was the Marquise herself) and came forward 
to welcome Emma. She made her sit down beside  

400
00:41:53,120 --> 00:41:58,240
her on a low chair, and began to chat with 
her, as if she had known her for a long time.

401
00:41:59,840 --> 00:42:05,440
At seven o'clock dinner was served. The men 
were seated at the first table, in the hall,  

402
00:42:05,440 --> 00:42:10,000
the ladies at the second, in the dining 
room, with the Marquis and the Marquise.  

403
00:42:11,200 --> 00:42:17,760
At the long dining tables, the glasses were filled 
with iced champagne. Emma felt a thrill go through  

404
00:42:17,760 --> 00:42:23,920
her as she tasted the coldness of it in her mouth. 
She had never seen some of the fruit that they had  

405
00:42:23,920 --> 00:42:29,840
on the table, and even the sugar seemed whiter 
here, and more finely powdered, than elsewhere.

406
00:42:31,600 --> 00:42:37,520
After dinner, there was dancing. More guests 
were arriving and the room filled with people.  

407
00:42:38,320 --> 00:42:43,760
Emma sat down near the door and watched the 
men talking and smoking cigars in small groups  

408
00:42:43,760 --> 00:42:48,880
in their black and white evening dress, as the 
servants moved among them carrying drinks and  

409
00:42:48,880 --> 00:42:55,680
more small, delicate things to eat. All along 
the rows of seated women she could see smiles  

410
00:42:55,680 --> 00:43:01,680
half-hidden, half-revealed, by the flowers 
the ladies held; everywhere there was silk,  

411
00:43:01,680 --> 00:43:07,760
the flash of jewels and gold, white arms, 
and hair piled high on elegant heads.

412
00:43:09,120 --> 00:43:14,720
Emma's heart beat faster when, her partner holding 
her by the tips of her fingers, she took her  

413
00:43:14,720 --> 00:43:21,360
place in line and stood waiting for the dance to 
begin. But her nervousness soon disappeared and,  

414
00:43:21,360 --> 00:43:28,720
moving to the music, she flew on as light as a 
bird. The memories of her past life, which until  

415
00:43:28,720 --> 00:43:34,160
then had always been so clear, disappeared 
so completely in the magic of the moment  

416
00:43:34,160 --> 00:43:41,360
that she could hardly persuade herself they were 
not a dream. There she was. No doubt about that!

417
00:43:43,360 --> 00:43:48,720
During a break in the dancing supper was 
served, and again the wine flowed freely,  

418
00:43:48,720 --> 00:43:54,160
accompanied by sea-food soup, sweet 
puddings and all kinds of cold meats.  

419
00:43:55,440 --> 00:43:59,040
Now people with longer journeys 
began to get into their carriages  

420
00:43:59,040 --> 00:44:04,160
and drive off one after another. Charles was 
half-asleep with his back against a door.  

421
00:44:04,800 --> 00:44:10,000
But not everyone was ready to leave, and it was 
at three in the morning when the last dance began.

422
00:44:11,280 --> 00:44:15,040
Only the guests who were staying the 
night at the chateau were still there.  

423
00:44:16,240 --> 00:44:22,480
One of these, a Viscount whose evening dress 
fitted him like a glove, came a second time to  

424
00:44:22,480 --> 00:44:28,720
invite Madame Bovary to dance. They began 
slowly, and then increased their speed.  

425
00:44:29,520 --> 00:44:34,400
They turned, and everything around them turned 
- the lamps, the furniture and the floor.  

426
00:44:35,200 --> 00:44:41,840
As they swung past the doors, Emma's dress blew 
up in the air. The Viscount looked down at her,  

427
00:44:41,840 --> 00:44:48,800
she raised her eyes to his; for a moment she lost 
her breath and stopped. Then off they went again,  

428
00:44:48,800 --> 00:44:54,480
quicker than ever, racing down to the high windows 
at the far end of the room, where she nearly fell  

429
00:44:54,480 --> 00:45:00,880
and, for a moment, rested her head on his chest. 
And then, still turning, but more gently now,  

430
00:45:01,440 --> 00:45:07,360
he took her to her seat. She leaned back against 
the wall and covered her eyes with her hands.  

431
00:45:09,040 --> 00:45:12,080
Then there was a little more conversation and,  

432
00:45:12,080 --> 00:45:18,000
after saying goodnight (or good 
morning), the guests went off to bed.

433
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:23,120
Charles dragged himself upstairs on 
heavy legs. But Emma did not want to  

434
00:45:23,120 --> 00:45:29,360
sleep. She opened the window and sat with 
her head in her hand. The night was dark.  

435
00:45:30,640 --> 00:45:36,960
A few drops of rain were falling. She breathed in 
the damp wind that blew cool against her eyelids.  

436
00:45:37,920 --> 00:45:40,880
The dance music was still playing in her ears,  

437
00:45:40,880 --> 00:45:45,840
and she tried to keep awake in order to keep 
the dream alive for as long as she could.  

438
00:45:46,560 --> 00:45:51,680
As she stood there, the sun began to rise 
beyond the trees and she shivered with cold.  

439
00:45:52,480 --> 00:45:57,520
She undressed and got down between the 
sheets, close up to Charles, who was asleep.

440
00:45:59,600 --> 00:46:04,000
There were twelve or fifteen of them at 
breakfast, which, to Charles's surprise,  

441
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:10,400
was all over in ten minutes. After that, a small 
group went with Mademoiselle d'Andervilliers for  

442
00:46:10,400 --> 00:46:16,880
a walk through the park, and then, to amuse the 
lady, the Marquis took Emma to see his stables,  

443
00:46:16,880 --> 00:46:20,400
while Charles went to ask one of the 
men to bring his horse and carriage.

444
00:46:21,920 --> 00:46:27,040
When Emma returned, the Bovarys said 
their goodbyes to the Marquis and Marquise  

445
00:46:27,040 --> 00:46:34,320
and turned their horse's head towards Tostes 
and home. Emma sat in silence. Their bags  

446
00:46:34,320 --> 00:46:38,000
banged against the back of the carriage as 
they made their way down the rough road.  

447
00:46:39,200 --> 00:46:44,160
They had reached the high ground at 
Thibourville when suddenly a group of gentlemen,  

448
00:46:44,160 --> 00:46:50,720
laughing and smoking cigars, rode past them. Emma 
thought she recognized the Viscount who had danced  

449
00:46:50,720 --> 00:46:56,400
with her last night. She turned round to have 
another look, but they were already too far away.

450
00:46:57,840 --> 00:47:01,120
A little later, they had to stop to 
make a small repair to the carriage.  

451
00:47:02,160 --> 00:47:08,080
When he had finished, Charles noticed something 
lying on the ground between his horse's legs. He  

452
00:47:08,080 --> 00:47:14,400
bent down and picked up a beautifully-made green 
silk cigar-case with two cigars still inside it.

453
00:47:16,160 --> 00:47:18,000
'They'll be good this evening after dinner.'

454
00:47:18,560 --> 00:47:21,200
He put the case in his 
pocket and started the horse.

455
00:47:23,120 --> 00:47:24,320
When they got home,  

456
00:47:24,320 --> 00:47:31,600
the evening meal was not ready. Madame became 
angry and the maid, Nastasie, replied rudely.

457
00:47:33,200 --> 00:47:35,920
'You can leave,' said Emma. 
'You are finished here!'

458
00:47:37,760 --> 00:47:42,480
So all they had for dinner was onion soup with 
a small piece of meat and some vegetables.

459
00:47:43,440 --> 00:47:46,800
'How nice it is to be back 
home again!' said Charles,  

460
00:47:46,800 --> 00:47:50,000
cheerfully rubbing his hands 
as he sat down opposite Emma.

461
00:47:51,360 --> 00:47:57,200
They could hear Nastasie weeping as they ate. 
Charles was rather fond of the poor girl,  

462
00:47:57,200 --> 00:48:01,200
who had kept him company after his first 
wife died, when he had nothing to do.  

463
00:48:02,400 --> 00:48:06,960
She had been his first patient, the first 
person he ever got to know in Tostes.

464
00:48:08,480 --> 00:48:11,520
'Have you really told her 
to leave?' he said at last.

465
00:48:12,560 --> 00:48:15,280
'Yes. Why not?' she replied.

466
00:48:16,880 --> 00:48:20,000
After supper, they went into the 
kitchen to warm themselves while  

467
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:26,240
the bedroom was being prepared. Charles 
began to smoke. He pushed out his lips,  

468
00:48:26,240 --> 00:48:31,040
spat repeatedly, and pulled his head back every 
time he breathed in the smoke from the cigar.

469
00:48:31,840 --> 00:48:33,840
'You'll make yourself ill!' she said.

470
00:48:35,440 --> 00:48:38,880
He put the cigar down, and went 
to get himself a drink of water.  

471
00:48:39,680 --> 00:48:44,160
Quick as lightning, Emma picked up the cigar-case 
and threw it into the back of the cupboard.

472
00:48:46,160 --> 00:48:52,560
Time went so slowly the next day! Emma 
walked around her little garden, up and down,  

473
00:48:52,560 --> 00:48:56,960
up and down, stopping to look at 
the flower-beds, at the fruit trees;  

474
00:48:56,960 --> 00:49:02,800
looking at all these familiar things, things that 
she knew so well but which now seemed so strange.  

475
00:49:04,160 --> 00:49:11,600
How far away the chateau seemed already! Her 
journey to La Vaubyessard had changed her life,  

476
00:49:11,600 --> 00:49:16,800
but left it feeling empty. 
However, she accepted her fate.  

477
00:49:17,840 --> 00:49:22,720
She folded up her beautiful dress and laid 
it carefully away in the chest of drawers,  

478
00:49:22,720 --> 00:49:29,840
with her dancing shoes. She had now known wealth 
and luxury, and life would never be the same.

479
00:49:31,520 --> 00:49:37,920
The memory of this visit to the chateau became 
part of her life. Each Wednesday she would sigh as  

480
00:49:37,920 --> 00:49:47,760
she awoke and say to herself, 'A week ago today... 
a fortnight ago... three weeks ago, I was there!'  

481
00:49:49,840 --> 00:49:55,440
But little by little the faces of the people 
became faint in her memory, and she forgot the  

482
00:49:55,440 --> 00:50:02,000
tunes she had danced to. The servants' clothes, 
the look of the rooms came back less clearly to  

483
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:11,840
her vision. Some of the details faded away, 
but the empty space in her heart remained.
 
 
 

484
00:50:12,640 --> 00:50:13,440
CHAPTER FIVE

485
00:50:14,160 --> 00:50:14,960
Moving Home

486
00:50:17,520 --> 00:50:22,000
Often, when Charles was out of the house, 
Emma would go to the cupboard and take  

487
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:27,920
out the green silk cigar-case she had hidden 
there. It must have belonged to the Viscount.  

488
00:50:28,960 --> 00:50:34,000
Perhaps it was a present from a lady friend in 
Paris, made with love and care in every stitch.  

489
00:50:35,200 --> 00:50:42,720
Paris! What sort of a place was it? 'Paris!' - 
she said the name under her breath, because she  

490
00:50:42,720 --> 00:50:48,400
loved the sound of it. It was like the great 
bell in an old church; the word seemed to add  

491
00:50:48,400 --> 00:50:54,320
a golden light to everything around it - even to 
the labels of her little pots of cheap make-up.

492
00:50:55,920 --> 00:51:00,400
She bought a guidebook to Paris and, with 
her fingertip on the map, she would make  

493
00:51:00,400 --> 00:51:07,120
little imaginary journeys around the capital. She 
pretended she was walking along the wide streets,  

494
00:51:07,120 --> 00:51:14,400
looking in wonder at the great houses. At last, 
growing tired, she would let her eyes close,  

495
00:51:14,400 --> 00:51:18,480
and then in the darkness she dreamed 
she saw the flame of the street lamps,  

496
00:51:18,480 --> 00:51:22,400
and the steps of the carriages being 
let down at the entrance to the theatre.

497
00:51:24,640 --> 00:51:27,360
She buried herself in women's magazines,  

498
00:51:27,360 --> 00:51:31,440
reading every word about opera and 
fashion and the life of the rich.  

499
00:51:32,640 --> 00:51:37,360
She read the latest novels - even bringing 
her book with her to the table and turning  

500
00:51:37,360 --> 00:51:44,320
the pages while Charles ate and talked. And as she 
read, the memory of the Viscount came back to her  

501
00:51:44,960 --> 00:51:50,720
and her dreams became more important, more real 
to her than her life as a country doctor's wife.

502
00:51:52,160 --> 00:51:57,680
But she tried to improve things in her house. 
She taught her maid to hand a glass of water  

503
00:51:57,680 --> 00:52:05,840
held in a white cloth, to knock before entering a 
room, to dress her mistress. In the daytime, Emma  

504
00:52:05,840 --> 00:52:12,640
wore a long dress with a silk belt and little red 
silk shoes. She had bought herself a writing-case,  

505
00:52:12,640 --> 00:52:19,760
a pen-holder and some envelopes, although she had 
no one to write to. She thought she would like to  

506
00:52:19,760 --> 00:52:27,520
travel, or to go back to her school. She wanted 
to die - and she wanted to go and live in Paris.

507
00:52:29,600 --> 00:52:36,160
And Charles rode from farm to farm on his old 
horse. He ate breakfast in farmhouse kitchens,  

508
00:52:36,720 --> 00:52:41,520
visited sick people in their dirty 
beds, got blood on his hands and face  

509
00:52:41,520 --> 00:52:48,880
and listened to the last words of the dying. But 
every night he came home to a fire, a good dinner,  

510
00:52:48,880 --> 00:52:54,080
a comfortable chair, and a pretty wife who 
had so many little ways of giving pleasure.  

511
00:52:55,200 --> 00:53:01,440
It might be paper shades for the candles, a new 
ribbon for her dress or an extraordinary name  

512
00:53:01,440 --> 00:53:06,400
for a very ordinary dish, which Charles 
ate happily, enjoying every bit of it.  

513
00:53:07,440 --> 00:53:11,680
Everything Emma did added something to the 
pleasure of his senses and of his home.  

514
00:53:12,640 --> 00:53:16,560
It was like finding gold-dust in the 
middle of the narrow pathway of his life.

515
00:53:17,760 --> 00:53:24,560
He felt well, and looked well. People liked 
him. He talked to their children, did not drink,  

516
00:53:25,120 --> 00:53:30,720
could be trusted and was especially good with the 
chest complaints that were so common among country  

517
00:53:30,720 --> 00:53:37,120
people. A major reason for Charles's success was 
that he was so afraid of killing his patients  

518
00:53:37,120 --> 00:53:42,960
that he never gave them anything more than simple 
medicines - but he was not frightened of surgery,  

519
00:53:42,960 --> 00:53:48,880
and had a strong wrist when he pulled teeth. The 
people of the region were happy with their doctor.

520
00:53:50,800 --> 00:53:56,880
Charles did have some ambitions. He tried to 
read a professional journal after dinner, but  

521
00:53:56,880 --> 00:54:01,840
the warmth of the room and the good meal he had 
eaten would send him to sleep after five minutes.  

522
00:54:02,800 --> 00:54:10,240
And there he sat, his head resting on his two 
hands and his long hair hanging over his face.  

523
00:54:10,240 --> 00:54:14,720
Emma looked at him and asked herself 
why she had not got one of those strong,  

524
00:54:14,720 --> 00:54:20,000
silent men for a husband, men who sit up at 
night with their books, and become famous,  

525
00:54:20,000 --> 00:54:26,240
if not rich. She would have liked the name 
of Bovary, which was hers now, to be famous,  

526
00:54:26,240 --> 00:54:29,600
to be seen in the bookshops, 
talked about in the papers,  

527
00:54:29,600 --> 00:54:36,160
known all over France. But Charles did not have 
that kind of ambition, and sometimes she felt  

528
00:54:36,160 --> 00:54:44,800
like hitting him. 'What a man! What a poor kind 
of man!' she said to herself, biting her lips.

529
00:54:46,880 --> 00:54:52,960
So as time went on, Emma felt herself less 
and less able to put up with her husband.  

530
00:54:54,160 --> 00:55:00,000
He was growing more unpleasant as he got older. He 
sucked his teeth after eating, and made a horrible  

531
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:05,920
noise at every mouthful of soup he swallowed. 
As he was beginning to put on weight, his eyes,  

532
00:55:05,920 --> 00:55:12,160
which were already small, looked as if they would 
start to disappear into his increasingly fat face.

533
00:55:13,680 --> 00:55:19,120
Deep down in her heart, she was waiting 
for something to happen. She did not know  

534
00:55:19,120 --> 00:55:25,120
what it would be, what the wind would blow 
to her. But every morning when she awoke,  

535
00:55:25,120 --> 00:55:31,360
she hoped it would come that day. She listened 
to every sound, watched every new face in the  

536
00:55:31,360 --> 00:55:37,920
street outside her house for a sign, and could 
not understand why nothing happened. And then  

537
00:55:38,640 --> 00:55:43,920
at sunset, sadder than ever, she 
would long for the next day to come.

538
00:55:47,440 --> 00:55:54,080
The spring came again. With the first touch of 
heat, when the apple trees were in flower, she  

539
00:55:54,080 --> 00:56:01,040
began to have attacks of dizziness. And when July 
came, she counted on her fingers how many weeks  

540
00:56:01,040 --> 00:56:06,160
it would be to October, thinking that perhaps 
the Marquis d'Andervilliers would be giving  

541
00:56:06,160 --> 00:56:13,520
another dance at La Vaubyessard. But September 
came and went, and no one called or wrote.

542
00:56:15,200 --> 00:56:21,040
After this disappointment there was the same 
emptiness in her heart, and the empty days began  

543
00:56:21,040 --> 00:56:28,160
again as before. The future was like a corridor 
in which there was no light, and at the end of it  

544
00:56:28,160 --> 00:56:36,080
only a closed door. She gave up her music. What 
was the use of playing? Who was there to hear?  

545
00:56:37,200 --> 00:56:43,840
She stopped her drawing. What was the good, what 
was the good of it all? Even sewing bored her.

546
00:56:44,800 --> 00:56:49,840
'There's nothing left to read,' she 
said to herself. And there she sat,  

547
00:56:49,840 --> 00:56:51,520
staring at the falling rain.

548
00:56:53,360 --> 00:56:59,840
Was this hopeless life going to last for ever? Was 
there no escape? She knew she was just as good as  

549
00:56:59,840 --> 00:57:06,320
the luckier ones. At La Vaubyessard she had seen 
great ladies who were not as pretty or intelligent  

550
00:57:06,320 --> 00:57:14,160
as her; why was she so unlucky? She would lean 
her head against the wall and weep, wanting so  

551
00:57:14,160 --> 00:57:20,080
much for a life of excitement, pleasures, all the 
delights which must be out there in the world,  

552
00:57:20,080 --> 00:57:27,280
but which were not hers. There were days when she 
would talk and talk; then the excitement would die  

553
00:57:27,280 --> 00:57:34,240
away, and she would fall back into a kind of dream 
world and sit without moving or saying a word.

554
00:57:36,560 --> 00:57:42,160
As she was always saying how she hated Tostes, 
Charles thought her illness must be caused by  

555
00:57:42,160 --> 00:57:49,360
the place itself. The idea grew on him, and he 
began seriously to think of going elsewhere.  

556
00:57:50,720 --> 00:57:53,840
Then she started drinking vinegar 
to make herself lose weight,  

557
00:57:54,640 --> 00:57:58,160
coughed a little dry cough 
and could not touch her food.

558
00:57:59,840 --> 00:58:05,600
It was hard for Charles to leave Tostes. He had 
been there for four years and was building a  

559
00:58:05,600 --> 00:58:13,840
good practice. However, what must be must be. 
He took her to Rouen to see another doctor.  

560
00:58:13,840 --> 00:58:20,560
The doctor said it was a case of nerves. What she 
needed was a change. So Charles looked around all  

561
00:58:20,560 --> 00:58:26,640
over the place, and at last heard of a busy little 
market town called Yonville-l'Abbaye, somewhere in  

562
00:58:26,640 --> 00:58:32,240
the Neufchatel area, where the doctor had recently 
left town and no replacement had been found.  

563
00:58:33,600 --> 00:58:39,440
He wrote to the local pharmacist asking him to let 
him know how many people there were in the place,  

564
00:58:39,440 --> 00:58:43,920
what sort of competition there was, and 
how much a year the other man used to make.  

565
00:58:45,040 --> 00:58:49,840
The answers were satisfactory, and Charles 
decided he would make a move in the spring  

566
00:58:50,400 --> 00:58:52,240
if Emma's health had not improved.

567
00:58:54,960 --> 00:58:58,320
One day, when she was emptying a 
drawer in preparation for the move,  

568
00:58:58,960 --> 00:59:05,520
Emma felt something sharp against her finger. It 
was the piece of wire around her wedding flowers,  

569
00:59:05,520 --> 00:59:11,760
faded and dusty now, and the ribbon eaten 
by insects. She threw them on the fire,  

570
00:59:11,760 --> 00:59:17,840
where they burned like a handful of dry grass 
and then lay like a red bush in the fireplace.  

571
00:59:18,480 --> 00:59:24,800
As she watched them burn, the paper berries 
burst, the wire bent and twisted, and the  

572
00:59:24,800 --> 00:59:31,840
paper flowers were held in the hot air like black 
insects until, at last, they flew up the chimney.

573
00:59:33,200 --> 00:59:37,760
In March, when they left Tostes, 
Madame Bovary was pregnant.
 
 
 

574
00:59:41,280 --> 00:59:42,160
CHAPTER SIX

575
00:59:43,040 --> 00:59:43,760
Yonville

576
00:59:45,520 --> 00:59:50,400
Yonville-l'Abbaye is a market town 
about twenty-six kilometres from Rouen,  

577
00:59:50,400 --> 00:59:52,720
between the Abbeville and Beauvais roads.  

578
00:59:53,760 --> 00:59:59,120
It is on the borders of Normandy, Picardy and 
the Ile-de-France, the sort of place where the  

579
00:59:59,120 --> 01:00:05,360
language has no accent and the landscape no 
character. Here they make the worst cheese in  

580
01:00:05,360 --> 01:00:11,440
the whole district, and farming is expensive 
because the sandy, stony soil is so poor.

581
01:00:12,960 --> 01:00:19,520
Until 1835 there was no good road to Yonville, 
and although a new one has been built, nothing has  

582
01:00:19,520 --> 01:00:26,240
really changed there for a hundred years. Walking 
into the town you still pass small farmhouses set  

583
01:00:26,240 --> 01:00:31,200
in their own gardens, and see that the fields 
stretch almost into the centre of the town.  

584
01:00:32,400 --> 01:00:38,000
The market, with its red roof supported by twenty 
or more wooden posts, takes up half of the town  

585
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:44,560
square. The Town Hall is a large, important 
looking building, but what really catches  

586
01:00:44,560 --> 01:00:50,640
the eye is the pharmacy of Monsieur Homais just 
opposite the town's one hotel, the Lion d'Or.

587
01:00:52,400 --> 01:00:57,520
The pharmacy is especially attractive at night 
when the lamps are lit and the big red and green  

588
01:00:57,520 --> 01:01:02,800
glass bottles in the window send long beams 
of coloured light far out along the ground.  

589
01:01:04,320 --> 01:01:09,120
From top to bottom, the building is covered with 
advertisements for medicines and mineral water,  

590
01:01:09,680 --> 01:01:15,760
and the shop-sign which goes right across the 
front carries in golden letters the words 'Homais,  

591
01:01:15,760 --> 01:01:22,560
Pharmacist'. At the far end of the shop, the word 
'Laboratory' appears over a glass door on which,  

592
01:01:22,560 --> 01:01:27,360
halfway up, the name 'Homais' is 
repeated in more gold letters on black.

593
01:01:28,720 --> 01:01:31,680
And that is all there is worth seeing in Yonville.  

594
01:01:32,560 --> 01:01:37,840
The one and only street, with a shop or two on 
either side of it, stops at the bend in the road.  

595
01:01:38,800 --> 01:01:43,680
If you turn to your right and follow the path at 
the foot of the hill, you come to the cemetery.

596
01:01:45,280 --> 01:01:50,320
The night the Bovarys arrived in Yonville, 
Madame Lefrancois, who ran the inn,  

597
01:01:50,320 --> 01:01:55,200
was so busy that the sweat ran down her face 
as she rushed around among her pots and pans.  

598
01:01:56,320 --> 01:02:00,480
Tomorrow was market day and she still 
had the meat to cook, the soup to make  

599
01:02:00,480 --> 01:02:05,280
and the coffee to get ready. Then there 
was the meal for her regular customers,  

600
01:02:05,280 --> 01:02:10,560
as well as for the new doctor and his wife and 
maid - whose coach was now half an hour late.

601
01:02:11,920 --> 01:02:17,280
Shouts of laughter came from the bar, where 
three workmen were calling for more wine  

602
01:02:17,280 --> 01:02:24,000
and the wood fire was burning. A man in soft 
green leather shoes, a smoking cap on his head,  

603
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:30,240
was standing warming his back by the fire. He had 
a look of complete self-satisfaction on his face,  

604
01:02:30,800 --> 01:02:36,720
and he appeared to be as carefree as the small 
bird in the cage which hung from the ceiling. It  

605
01:02:36,720 --> 01:02:41,440
was the pharmacist, waiting for the evening 
meal which he regularly ate at the hotel.

606
01:02:43,040 --> 01:02:47,760
He did not have to wait too long. 
Soon, Madame Lefrancois heard the  

607
01:02:47,760 --> 01:02:52,240
sound of wheels and the metal shoes 
of a tired horse on the road outside.

608
01:02:53,760 --> 01:02:59,600
As soon as the coach stopped, other villagers 
came to the inn, and all began to speak at once,  

609
01:02:59,600 --> 01:03:03,360
asking for news, explanations and 
packages they had been waiting for.  

610
01:03:04,560 --> 01:03:08,960
As he gave out his parcels, Hivert, 
the coachman, told them they had been  

611
01:03:08,960 --> 01:03:13,920
delayed because Madame Bovary's little 
dog had run away and had not been found.

612
01:03:15,520 --> 01:03:21,120
Emma had, in fact, been crying for the 
last hour. She said it was Charles's fault.  

613
01:03:21,920 --> 01:03:26,960
Monsieur Lheureux, who was travelling inside the 
coach and who had the fabric shop in the village,  

614
01:03:26,960 --> 01:03:31,200
had done his best to make her happier 
by telling her of several cases in which  

615
01:03:31,200 --> 01:03:36,640
dogs had come back to their masters after 
years of separation. There was a story,  

616
01:03:36,640 --> 01:03:41,360
he said, of a dog that found its way back 
to Paris all the way from Constantinople!

617
01:03:42,960 --> 01:03:50,400
Dog or no dog, they had arrived at their new home, 
and had to leave the coach. Emma got out first,  

618
01:03:50,960 --> 01:03:57,280
then Felicite, her maid, and then Monsieur 
Lheureux. They had to wake Charles up;  

619
01:03:57,280 --> 01:04:00,400
he had fallen asleep in his 
corner as soon as it grew dark.

620
01:04:01,600 --> 01:04:07,200
Homais introduced himself, offered his services 
to Madame and his respects to Monsieur,  

621
01:04:07,200 --> 01:04:10,480
told them he was charmed to have 
been able to do them a service,  

622
01:04:10,480 --> 01:04:14,960
adding with a smile that he had invited himself 
to dinner as his wife was away from home.

623
01:04:16,720 --> 01:04:20,560
As soon as she was in the kitchen, 
Madame Bovary went over to the fire.  

624
01:04:21,440 --> 01:04:26,160
With the tips of two fingers she took hold of 
her dress at the knee and, raising it above  

625
01:04:26,160 --> 01:04:34,160
her ankles, stretched out a foot to the flames - a 
little foot in a black boot. The fire lit her from  

626
01:04:34,160 --> 01:04:40,240
top to toe, its red light making her dress shine 
and showing the perfect white skin of her face.  

627
01:04:41,920 --> 01:04:47,200
On the other side of the fireplace, a 
fair-haired young man watched her in silence.

628
01:04:49,120 --> 01:04:55,760
Monsieur Leon Dupuis, clerk to the town's only 
lawyer, also ate regularly at the Lion d'Or.  

629
01:04:56,960 --> 01:05:00,560
As he found life in Yonville 
almost impossibly boring,  

630
01:05:00,560 --> 01:05:04,400
he would often delay his meal in the hope 
that a traveller would arrive at the inn  

631
01:05:04,400 --> 01:05:09,680
with whom he could enjoy a conversation 
in the evening. It was therefore with some  

632
01:05:09,680 --> 01:05:13,920
pleasure that he accepted the suggestion 
that he should sit down with the Bovarys.

633
01:05:15,760 --> 01:05:21,840
At the table, Homais asked permission to 
keep on his cap, for fear of catching cold.

634
01:05:21,840 --> 01:05:27,520
'Madame must be a little tired,' he said, turning 
to Emma. 'It is not a comfortable journey.'

635
01:05:28,960 --> 01:05:36,080
'Very true,' she answered, 'but I love 
moving around. I hate staying in one place.'

636
01:05:36,080 --> 01:05:40,400
'Oh, I agree. Staying in one place 
is horrible!' said the clerk.

637
01:05:41,680 --> 01:05:45,840
'But if you were like me,' said Charles, 
'and always had to be on your horse...'

638
01:05:47,120 --> 01:05:52,800
And so the meal continued. Charles spent most 
of his time discussing medical matters with  

639
01:05:52,800 --> 01:05:58,000
Monsieur Homais, while Leon told Madame Bovary 
about the attractions of the neighbourhood.  

640
01:05:59,040 --> 01:06:04,160
They quickly discovered that they 
shared the same romantic tastes.

641
01:06:04,160 --> 01:06:10,320
'I think there's nothing so beautiful as a sunset, 
especially by the sea!' said Madame Bovary.

642
01:06:11,200 --> 01:06:14,880
'Oh, I love the sea!' Monsieur Leon replied.

643
01:06:16,480 --> 01:06:20,480
'And doesn't it seem to you, 
somehow, that you think more freely,  

644
01:06:20,480 --> 01:06:24,720
and that it raises your soul and makes you 
think of the endless nature of things?'

645
01:06:26,080 --> 01:06:29,360
'It's just the same where there 
are mountains,' Leon went on.

646
01:06:30,640 --> 01:06:37,200
So they continued talking of Switzerland and 
Italy, which they had never visited, and music,  

647
01:06:37,200 --> 01:06:38,720
which neither of them could play,  

648
01:06:39,440 --> 01:06:43,760
and reading - the one thing that 
both of them did enthusiastically.

649
01:06:45,360 --> 01:06:49,120
'What can be better than sitting by 
the fire in the evening with a book,  

650
01:06:49,120 --> 01:06:53,280
when the lamp is lit and the wind 
beats against the window?' said Leon.

651
01:06:54,480 --> 01:06:59,840
'That's just what I think,' she replied, 
looking at him with her big, dark eyes.

652
01:07:01,040 --> 01:07:08,400
'You forget everything,' he went on. 'The 
hours slip by. Sitting still in your armchair,  

653
01:07:08,400 --> 01:07:14,160
you can wander in strange places and 
imagine they are there before your eyes.'

654
01:07:14,160 --> 01:07:16,240
'Oh yes, that's true!' she said.

655
01:07:17,840 --> 01:07:21,280
They had been at the table for 
two and a half hours by now,  

656
01:07:21,280 --> 01:07:25,840
since Artemise, the servant, did not hurry as 
she brought the dishes in from the kitchen.  

657
01:07:27,280 --> 01:07:32,000
Quite unconsciously, Leon had put his foot 
up on one of the bars of the chair on which  

658
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:36,720
Madame Bovary was sitting, moving closer 
so he could catch everything she said.  

659
01:07:37,840 --> 01:07:43,360
And so, while Charles and the pharmacist went on 
with their discussion, Emma and Leon sat close  

660
01:07:43,360 --> 01:07:48,720
to one another, and entered into a conversation in 
which they talked about the interests they shared:  

661
01:07:49,520 --> 01:07:56,000
the Paris theatres, names of novels, the latest 
dances, the world of fashion, which neither of  

662
01:07:56,000 --> 01:08:01,760
them knew anything about, Tostes, where she 
had lived, and Yonville, where they were now.  

663
01:08:02,880 --> 01:08:07,520
They discussed anything and everything, 
and talked all through dinner.

664
01:08:09,280 --> 01:08:14,240
When the coffee was brought in, Felicite 
went to arrange the bedroom in the new house,  

665
01:08:14,240 --> 01:08:17,920
and the group around the dinner 
table soon afterwards rose to go.  

666
01:08:19,040 --> 01:08:22,240
Madame Lefrancois had fallen 
asleep by the dying fire,  

667
01:08:22,800 --> 01:08:28,320
while the manservant, lamp in hand, was waiting 
to show Monsieur and Madame Bovary to their house.

668
01:08:29,920 --> 01:08:36,640
The house felt damp and cold after the warmth of 
the inn. The walls were new and the wooden stairs  

669
01:08:36,640 --> 01:08:43,200
had no carpet. Upstairs in the bedroom, a pale 
light came in through the curtainless windows.  

670
01:08:43,920 --> 01:08:49,280
The tops of some trees could just be seen, 
and beyond them, the fields in the moonlight.

671
01:08:50,640 --> 01:08:56,080
This would be the fourth time Emma had slept in 
a new bedroom. The first was when she went to the  

672
01:08:56,080 --> 01:09:02,480
convent, the second when she came to Tostes, 
the third at La Vaubyessard, and now this was  

673
01:09:02,480 --> 01:09:07,920
the fourth. And every time, it had seemed as 
if she were entering a new stage in her life.  

674
01:09:08,720 --> 01:09:14,480
She could not believe that things would look 
and be the same in different places. The most  

675
01:09:14,480 --> 01:09:19,840
recent period of her life had been bad, so 
the next part would have to be better.
 
 
 

676
01:09:23,600 --> 01:09:24,480
CHAPTER SEVEN

677
01:09:25,760 --> 01:09:26,400
In Love

678
01:09:29,920 --> 01:09:36,000
Next morning, when she awoke, Emma saw the 
clerk walking across the square. She was in her  

679
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:42,880
dressing-gown. He looked up and took off his hat. 
She gave a little nod and quickly shut the window.

680
01:09:44,640 --> 01:09:50,480
All day long, Leon waited for six o'clock to 
arrive. But when he went round to the inn,  

681
01:09:50,480 --> 01:09:55,440
the only person there was Monsieur Binet, the 
tax collector, already seated at the table.  

682
01:09:56,720 --> 01:10:01,840
The dinner of the night before had been an 
important event for Leon. It was the first time in  

683
01:10:01,840 --> 01:10:08,720
his life that he had talked to a woman for a whole 
evening. How did he manage to tell her, and in  

684
01:10:08,720 --> 01:10:15,680
such brilliant language, so many things he could 
not have expressed so well before? Unfortunately,  

685
01:10:15,680 --> 01:10:19,680
it did not look as if he would have the chance 
to repeat his performance for the moment.

686
01:10:21,280 --> 01:10:26,480
Monsieur Homais, the pharmacist, however, was 
able to visit Madame Bovary and show what a  

687
01:10:26,480 --> 01:10:32,800
good neighbour he was. He told her all about the 
shopkeepers, where to get her butter cheaply,  

688
01:10:32,800 --> 01:10:38,240
and he helped her find a gardener. It has to 
be said, however, that he was not doing this  

689
01:10:38,240 --> 01:10:44,480
out of pure kindness. Monsieur Homais had, 
a year earlier, broken the law which forbade  

690
01:10:44,480 --> 01:10:50,560
the practice of medicine by all unqualified 
persons. Someone had told the authorities,  

691
01:10:50,560 --> 01:10:55,360
and Monsieur Homais had been given a very 
severe warning by the magistrate in Rouen.  

692
01:10:56,480 --> 01:11:01,040
The problem was that he still liked to give 
quick, innocent consultations in his shop,  

693
01:11:01,600 --> 01:11:08,720
but the Mayor did not like him, others were 
jealous, and he was playing a dangerous game. So  

694
01:11:08,720 --> 01:11:13,520
Monsieur Homais thought to himself that if he did 
things for Monsieur and Madame Bovary, Monsieur  

695
01:11:13,520 --> 01:11:19,560
Bovary would be grateful, and a grateful man does 
not make complaints to the authorities in Rouen.

696
01:11:21,040 --> 01:11:26,640
Every morning, Homais would come across with 
the newspaper and often, during the afternoon,  

697
01:11:26,640 --> 01:11:29,920
he would leave his shop for a minute 
or two to chat with the new doctor.  

698
01:11:31,360 --> 01:11:38,400
Charles was not a happy man; patients did not 
come. He sat for hour after hour in silence,  

699
01:11:38,400 --> 01:11:44,320
or he went to sleep in his surgery or watched 
his wife sew. He even started doing some small  

700
01:11:44,320 --> 01:11:48,480
jobs at home, trying to paint the bedroom 
with some paint the men had left behind.  

701
01:11:49,360 --> 01:11:55,040
Money was his great worry. He had spent 
such a lot on repairs at Tostes, on his  

702
01:11:55,040 --> 01:12:01,600
wife's clothes and on moving, and most of his 
savings and Emma's money had gone in two years.

703
01:12:03,520 --> 01:12:06,880
But Charles also had something 
pleasant to think about,  

704
01:12:06,880 --> 01:12:11,600
as his wife was expecting a child, 
and the closer they got to the time,  

705
01:12:11,600 --> 01:12:18,080
the more loving he became. It was another link 
between them, real evidence of their marriage.  

706
01:12:19,520 --> 01:12:25,120
When he watched her heavier walk, when she sat 
opposite him at the table, or when she was in her  

707
01:12:25,120 --> 01:12:31,040
armchair after dinner, he could not stop himself 
getting up, kissing her, stroking her face,  

708
01:12:31,600 --> 01:12:39,040
calling her 'little mother'. The idea of being a 
father pleased him very much. He lacked nothing.

709
01:12:41,040 --> 01:12:47,680
At first Emma was surprised by his attention; then 
all she wanted was to have the baby as soon as  

710
01:12:47,680 --> 01:12:54,560
possible, so that she would know how it felt to 
be a mother. Their shortage of money meant that  

711
01:12:54,560 --> 01:12:59,680
she could not buy all the things she wanted for 
the new arrival, so perhaps she did not feel as  

712
01:12:59,680 --> 01:13:05,520
much love for the child she carried as she wanted 
to give. But she thought about it all the time.

713
01:13:06,400 --> 01:13:12,000
She hoped it would be a boy. He should be 
strong and dark, and they would call him  

714
01:13:12,000 --> 01:13:16,240
George. And the thought of having 
a boy somehow made her feel better.  

715
01:13:16,960 --> 01:13:22,400
A man would be free, while a woman 
is always limited. She is weaker and  

716
01:13:22,400 --> 01:13:27,440
economically dependent, and the habits of 
society do not permit her the same freedom.

717
01:13:30,160 --> 01:13:35,840
Emma's baby was born on a Sunday morning 
at about six, just as the sun was rising.

718
01:13:37,360 --> 01:13:39,680
'It's a girl,' said Charles.

719
01:13:41,120 --> 01:13:43,680
She turned away her head and fainted.

720
01:13:45,120 --> 01:13:50,720
Madame Homais came to the house as soon as the 
news was given to congratulate her, and so did  

721
01:13:50,720 --> 01:13:57,280
Madame Lefrancois of the Lion d'Or. The pharmacist 
offered his congratulations through the half-open  

722
01:13:57,280 --> 01:14:03,120
door. He then asked to see the baby and declared 
it was the most well formed he had ever seen.

723
01:14:05,040 --> 01:14:08,960
As the doctor felt that his wife was not 
strong enough to feed the baby herself,  

724
01:14:09,680 --> 01:14:15,760
the little girl was sent to a wet nurse. With 
nothing else to do in the days after the birth,  

725
01:14:16,400 --> 01:14:21,840
Emma tried to think of a name for her daughter. 
First she went through names with Italian endings,  

726
01:14:21,840 --> 01:14:31,040
like Clara, Louisa, Amanda. She rather liked 
old names like Galsuinde, or Yseult or Leocadie.  

727
01:14:32,160 --> 01:14:36,400
Charles wanted the child to be called 
after her mother. Emma said no.

728
01:14:38,400 --> 01:14:42,640
At last Emma remembered that at 
the Chateau de la Vaubyessard  

729
01:14:42,640 --> 01:14:49,040
she had heard the Marquise call a young woman 
by the name of Berthe. That decision was made.

730
01:14:51,280 --> 01:14:55,840
Four or five weeks after the birth, Emma 
felt a sudden need to see her little girl,  

731
01:14:56,640 --> 01:15:00,880
so she set out in the direction of the wet 
nurse's house at the far end of the village.  

732
01:15:02,000 --> 01:15:08,720
It was midday and the sun beat down from 
a cloudless sky. A hot wind was blowing  

733
01:15:08,720 --> 01:15:13,200
and when she had gone some way, Emma began 
to feel weak from the effort of walking.  

734
01:15:14,400 --> 01:15:18,240
She started to think she should return 
home or go in somewhere and sit down.

735
01:15:20,160 --> 01:15:24,640
Just then, Monsieur Leon came out from 
a house close by, with some papers under  

736
01:15:24,640 --> 01:15:31,840
his arm. He came up and spoke, and took her into 
the shade outside Lheureux's shop. Madame Bovary  

737
01:15:31,840 --> 01:15:36,000
said she was on her way to see her baby, 
but that she was beginning to feel tired.

738
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:42,000
'If...' began Leon, but he 
stopped, not daring to continue.

739
01:15:43,520 --> 01:15:45,760
'Are you very busy?' she asked.

740
01:15:46,720 --> 01:15:51,840
And when the clerk said that he was 
not, she begged him to walk with her.

741
01:15:52,400 --> 01:15:57,120
To reach the nurse's house they had to go along 
to the end of the street and then turn, as if  

742
01:15:57,120 --> 01:16:03,120
they were going to the cemetery. They set off side 
by side, and recognized the house by an old tree  

743
01:16:03,120 --> 01:16:09,920
that shaded it. It was a low, badly maintained 
house with a brown roof and small, untidy garden.

744
01:16:11,520 --> 01:16:17,360
Hearing the gate open, the woman came out, 
carrying a baby at her breast. With her other hand  

745
01:16:17,360 --> 01:16:22,560
she was dragging along a poor, miserable-looking 
two-year-old with spots all over his face.

746
01:16:23,760 --> 01:16:27,920
'Come in,' she said. 'Your 
little one is in there asleep.'

747
01:16:30,160 --> 01:16:35,760
She went into the dark bedroom, and showed 
Emma where the little girl was sleeping. Emma  

748
01:16:35,760 --> 01:16:42,080
took the baby in her arms, wrapped up in a dirty 
blanket, and began to sing gently as she held her.

749
01:16:43,120 --> 01:16:49,040
Leon walked up and down the room. It seemed 
strange to him to see this beautiful, elegantly  

750
01:16:49,040 --> 01:16:55,440
dressed woman in such poor surroundings. Madame 
Bovary saw him looking and blushed bright red.  

751
01:16:56,400 --> 01:17:00,000
He turned away, thinking he 
had perhaps seemed too curious,  

752
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:04,880
as she gave the baby back to the nurse. 
It had just been sick all over her collar.

753
01:17:06,320 --> 01:17:11,280
Having lost enthusiasm for her baby, 
Emma again took Monsieur Leon's arm,  

754
01:17:11,280 --> 01:17:15,840
and they left the nurse holding the child 
and waving as they went down the path.  

755
01:17:17,120 --> 01:17:24,000
Emma walked quickly for some distance, 
then slowed down. As she looked around her,  

756
01:17:24,000 --> 01:17:30,160
her eyes rested on the young man's shoulder and 
on his well-cut coat with its smart black collar.  

757
01:17:30,160 --> 01:17:35,520
She noticed how his golden brown hair was 
smooth and carefully brushed, and that his  

758
01:17:35,520 --> 01:17:40,640
fingernails were longer and much more carefully 
cared for than most fingernails in Yonville.

759
01:17:42,080 --> 01:17:48,160
They went back to the village on the path beside 
the river. The stream flowed on noiselessly,  

760
01:17:48,160 --> 01:17:54,640
deep and cool; dark plants moved in the water 
like long green hair, and insects walked over  

761
01:17:54,640 --> 01:17:59,920
its smooth surface or waited with shining 
wings on the tall grass at the water's edge.  

762
01:18:01,440 --> 01:18:07,920
All around, as far as the eye could see, the 
fields had emptied of people. It was dinner-time  

763
01:18:07,920 --> 01:18:13,120
in the farms, and the only sounds that fell on 
the ears of the young woman and her companion  

764
01:18:13,120 --> 01:18:19,840
were their footsteps on the path, the words they 
spoke and Emma's dress brushing against the grass.  

765
01:18:21,120 --> 01:18:26,560
The garden walls were hot in the sun, and the 
wild plants that were growing between the stones  

766
01:18:26,560 --> 01:18:32,720
had died. As she passed, Madame Bovary 
touched some of their dry flowers,  

767
01:18:32,720 --> 01:18:34,720
which made them fall into yellow dust.

768
01:18:36,560 --> 01:18:42,040
They were talking about some Spanish dancers who 
were going to perform at the theatre in Rouen.

769
01:18:42,800 --> 01:18:44,560
'Will you go?' she asked.

770
01:18:45,440 --> 01:18:47,040
'If I can,' he replied.

771
01:18:48,480 --> 01:18:53,520
Was this all they had to say to one 
another? They tried to speak of ordinary,  

772
01:18:53,520 --> 01:18:58,080
everyday things, but all the time they 
felt a deep change coming over them.  

773
01:18:58,880 --> 01:19:05,840
It was like a whisper from the soul, deep down, 
stronger than the spoken word. Lost in wonder  

774
01:19:05,840 --> 01:19:11,120
at this strange sweetness, they did not speak 
of it or try to explain what was happening.  

775
01:19:12,000 --> 01:19:15,920
But both felt that there could be 
future pleasures waiting for them.

776
01:19:17,680 --> 01:19:22,080
When they came to her garden, Madame 
Bovary pushed open the little gate  

777
01:19:22,080 --> 01:19:24,800
and, running up the steps, disappeared from view.

778
01:19:27,120 --> 01:19:33,520
Leon went back to his office. His boss was out. 
He looked quickly at some papers, prepared a  

779
01:19:33,520 --> 01:19:40,320
pen for writing, but then put on his hat and 
went out. He went up to the edge of the woods,  

780
01:19:40,320 --> 01:19:45,680
threw himself down on the ground under the 
trees and looked at the sky through his fingers.

781
01:19:48,240 --> 01:19:51,760
'Oh!' he sighed. 'I am so bored!'

782
01:19:55,760 --> 01:20:02,320
As soon as the weather began to turn cold, Emma 
spent her days in the sitting room. It was a long  

783
01:20:02,320 --> 01:20:08,000
room with a low ceiling, and above the fireplace 
there was a picture of the sea and a large mirror.  

784
01:20:09,040 --> 01:20:12,480
She pulled her chair close to the window 
so that she could watch the villagers  

785
01:20:12,480 --> 01:20:14,080
as they went by on the pavement.

786
01:20:15,760 --> 01:20:19,280
Twice a day, Leon passed from 
his work to the Lion d'Or.  

787
01:20:20,400 --> 01:20:25,760
Emma could recognize his steps from a long 
way away. She leaned forward and listened,  

788
01:20:25,760 --> 01:20:32,000
and the young man walked past, always dressed the 
same and always looking straight in front of him.  

789
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:36,480
In the evening, when she had dropped her piece 
of unfinished sewing on her lap and was sitting  

790
01:20:36,480 --> 01:20:42,240
with her chin resting on her left hand, she would 
again notice his figure moving past the window,  

791
01:20:42,800 --> 01:20:46,320
and then she would get up and tell 
the girl to lay the table for dinner.

792
01:20:48,160 --> 01:20:54,160
Monsieur Homais would often come in while they 
were eating. Smoking cap in hand, he would come in  

793
01:20:54,160 --> 01:21:00,720
quietly, not wanting to disturb anyone, and always 
saying the same thing: 'Good evening, everybody.'  

794
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:06,960
Having taken his usual place at the table, 
between husband and wife, he asked the doctor  

795
01:21:06,960 --> 01:21:11,840
about his patients, and the doctor consulted 
him about the sort of fees he ought to charge.  

796
01:21:12,960 --> 01:21:18,640
Then they began to discuss the news in the paper. 
At eight o'clock the pharmacist's assistant,  

797
01:21:18,640 --> 01:21:22,240
Justin, would come for him to 
go over and shut up the shop.

798
01:21:23,760 --> 01:21:29,280
On Sundays, the Bovarys would return these 
visits and spend the evening at the pharmacist's.  

799
01:21:30,240 --> 01:21:36,480
They would begin with cards - Monsieur Homais 
usually being Emma's partner. Leon would stand  

800
01:21:36,480 --> 01:21:43,280
behind her and tell her what to play. Every time 
she threw a card on the table, the movement would  

801
01:21:43,280 --> 01:21:49,520
pull up her dress on the right side, and her hair 
would move across her neck like soft brown silk.

802
01:21:51,360 --> 01:21:56,320
When they had finished the cards, the pharmacist 
and the doctor would settle down to discuss  

803
01:21:56,320 --> 01:22:01,920
the news of the day and drink their wine and 
Emma, changing her place, would sit with her  

804
01:22:01,920 --> 01:22:09,520
elbow on the table, turning over the pages of an 
illustrated magazine. Leon sat down beside her,  

805
01:22:09,520 --> 01:22:13,840
and they looked at the pictures together, 
waiting for each other at the bottom of the page.  

806
01:22:14,960 --> 01:22:21,360
Sometimes she would ask him to read some poetry. 
And so a kind of friendship began between them.

807
01:22:23,120 --> 01:22:28,320
The problem for Leon, however, was to know 
what sort of friend Madame Bovary might be.  

808
01:22:29,680 --> 01:22:34,240
They gave each other small presents, 
they were happy in each other's company,  

809
01:22:34,240 --> 01:22:39,040
but would there be more? He thought 
and thought about this in his lonely  

810
01:22:39,040 --> 01:22:44,880
room. Should he tell her what he was 
feeling? Did he love her, or didn't he?  

811
01:22:45,840 --> 01:22:50,160
He was torn between fear of hurting her 
and shame at his own lack of courage.  

812
01:22:51,120 --> 01:22:57,280
Sometimes he would make up his mind to act, and to 
act quickly. He wrote letters - and tore them up;  

813
01:22:57,840 --> 01:23:04,080
decided on a day to speak to her - and put it off. 
Sometimes he walked out of the lawyer's office  

814
01:23:04,080 --> 01:23:10,720
with his mind made up. But all his courage melted 
when he found himself face to face with Emma;  

815
01:23:10,720 --> 01:23:15,360
and when Charles came home and invited him 
to come with him to see a patient at a farm  

816
01:23:15,360 --> 01:23:22,240
a few kilometres away, he at once accepted and, 
with a bow to Madame, left with her husband.

817
01:23:23,520 --> 01:23:26,160
But Emma did not ask herself if she was in love.  

818
01:23:27,200 --> 01:23:32,800
Love, she thought, was something that must come 
suddenly, like a great thunderstorm, blowing away  

819
01:23:32,800 --> 01:23:39,280
your old life and carrying your heart and soul 
away, to heaven or to hell. She never thought  

820
01:23:39,280 --> 01:23:45,360
about the way a river can rise slowly, getting 
higher day by day, until after a night of rain it  

821
01:23:45,360 --> 01:23:53,680
breaks its banks and floods the land around it. In 
fact, she had no idea of the danger she was in.
 
 
 

822
01:23:57,280 --> 01:23:58,080
CHAPTER EIGHT

823
01:23:59,040 --> 01:24:01,840
A Dream Ends

824
01:24:02,800 --> 01:24:10,000
One snowy Sunday afternoon in February, Monsieur 
and Madame Bovary, Homais and Monsieur Leon  

825
01:24:10,000 --> 01:24:13,760
went to look at a new mill that 
was being built outside Yonville.  

826
01:24:14,880 --> 01:24:21,120
Homais had brought his children, to give them a 
little exercise. The place did not interest Emma,  

827
01:24:21,120 --> 01:24:26,960
and she stood away from the group, leaning on 
Leon's arm, while Homais and her husband talked  

828
01:24:26,960 --> 01:24:33,200
about the technical wonders - the thick walls, 
the great machinery - they saw all around them.

829
01:24:34,800 --> 01:24:40,240
Turning from the pale sunlight coming through 
the mist, she saw Charles, his cap pulled down  

830
01:24:40,240 --> 01:24:48,240
over his ears, his thick lips and his stupid face. 
Even his back was annoying, a stupid back covered  

831
01:24:48,240 --> 01:24:56,320
in a stupid, boring winter coat. Leon moved 
forward a step. The cold air had made him pale,  

832
01:24:56,320 --> 01:25:01,120
even more beautiful than normal. The 
collar of his shirt was open a little,  

833
01:25:01,120 --> 01:25:05,600
showing his white skin; the tip of his 
ear was visible under his long hair,  

834
01:25:06,400 --> 01:25:11,840
and his big blue eyes, raised upwards to 
the clouds, seemed to Emma to be clearer,  

835
01:25:12,400 --> 01:25:16,640
more beautiful than those mountain 
lakes in which the skies are mirrored.

836
01:25:18,640 --> 01:25:24,080
Madame Bovary did not go over to her neighbours' 
that evening, and when Charles had left and she  

837
01:25:24,080 --> 01:25:30,000
felt she was all alone, she lay down on the carpet 
in front of the fire and thought about Leon once  

838
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:38,000
more. She thought he was charming. She could not 
put him out of her thoughts. She remembered how he  

839
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:45,920
had stood, the things he had said, all about him. 
And she said over and over again, 'Oh, charming!  

840
01:25:46,720 --> 01:25:56,160
Charming!... And in love?' she asked herself. 
'But with whom?... But it must be with me!'

841
01:25:57,760 --> 01:26:02,080
The evidence was suddenly clear to 
her and her heart gave a great leap.  

842
01:26:02,880 --> 01:26:07,840
The firelight became brighter, and she turned 
on her back and stretched out her arms.

843
01:26:09,760 --> 01:26:14,000
After the first excitement, she then 
thought, as so many people have before,  

844
01:26:15,120 --> 01:26:22,320
'Ah, why did this happen when it was too 
late? Why not before? What prevented it?'

845
01:26:24,400 --> 01:26:26,480
It was midnight when Charles got back.  

846
01:26:27,840 --> 01:26:31,920
She pretended she had just woken up 
and, as he made a noise undressing,  

847
01:26:32,480 --> 01:26:37,280
she complained of having a headache. Then she 
asked what sort of an evening it had been.

848
01:26:39,080 --> 01:26:42,720
'Monsieur Leon,' he said, 'went to bed early.'

849
01:26:45,200 --> 01:26:50,080
She could not help smiling. When 
she turned over to go to sleep,  

850
01:26:50,080 --> 01:26:52,560
her heart was filled with a new happiness.

851
01:26:54,720 --> 01:27:00,560
Next day, however, she could not settle to her 
work in the house; she was happy, but still could  

852
01:27:00,560 --> 01:27:06,560
not take pleasure in the things she usually liked 
to do. So when Monsieur Lheureux, the draper,  

853
01:27:06,560 --> 01:27:13,600
visited and showed her a beautiful scarf, even 
offering to let her pay later, she refused. And  

854
01:27:13,600 --> 01:27:18,960
when Leon visited her in the afternoon, all 
she could do was to talk about her husband!

855
01:27:19,920 --> 01:27:26,320
The same sort of thing went on for days. Her 
manner and conversation changed completely.  

856
01:27:26,320 --> 01:27:30,720
She became interested in housekeeping, 
started going to church again regularly,  

857
01:27:31,360 --> 01:27:37,440
and stopped the cook stealing the sugar. She even 
took her little daughter Berthe away from the wet  

858
01:27:37,440 --> 01:27:44,400
nurse and showed her to all her visitors. She told 
everyone she loved children. They were such a joy  

859
01:27:44,400 --> 01:27:50,560
and comfort, she said, as she kissed the child 
and held her close to her. When Charles got home,  

860
01:27:50,560 --> 01:27:56,080
he would find his chair ready by the fire. His 
clothes were brushed and cleaned, the buttons  

861
01:27:56,080 --> 01:28:00,960
were always on his shirts, and his shirts were 
folded carefully after they had been ironed.  

862
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:06,160
When Leon saw him at the fireside after 
dinner, with his hands on his stomach,  

863
01:28:06,160 --> 01:28:11,440
his cheeks red from the meat and wine, 
the child crawling around on the carpet,  

864
01:28:11,440 --> 01:28:15,440
and this elegant woman who would lean over 
and kiss him over the back of the chair,  

865
01:28:16,160 --> 01:28:22,400
he would say to himself, 'What a fool I am 
to imagine I could make her care for me!'

866
01:28:24,960 --> 01:28:32,560
And as each day passed, Emma became thinner and 
paler. She was so sad and so calm, so gentle  

867
01:28:33,200 --> 01:28:38,240
and, at the same time, so distant, that you 
felt a sort of icy charm when you were with her.  

868
01:28:39,440 --> 01:28:42,320
This charm changed the 
attitudes of her neighbours;  

869
01:28:42,320 --> 01:28:46,320
they no longer saw her as the outsider 
who did not know how to behave properly.

870
01:28:47,600 --> 01:28:53,280
'She's a wonderful woman,' said the pharmacist, 
and the married women of Yonville admired her for  

871
01:28:53,280 --> 01:29:00,320
her good management, the patients for her pleasant 
manners, the poor for her charity. But beneath her  

872
01:29:00,320 --> 01:29:08,400
calm, Emma was in a state of desire and anger and 
hatred. Her plain, simple dress hid a heart that  

873
01:29:08,400 --> 01:29:15,840
was breaking, and she could tell no one, no one! 
She was in love with Leon, but she did not want to  

874
01:29:15,840 --> 01:29:21,120
see him. Her heart beat faster when she heard 
him coming, and then, when he was there, the  

875
01:29:21,120 --> 01:29:27,280
excitement went away and was replaced by a feeling 
of fear and sadness. She did not know what to do.

876
01:29:28,320 --> 01:29:33,520
What made it harder to bear was that Charles had 
no understanding of what she was going through,  

877
01:29:33,520 --> 01:29:35,840
and she began to hate him for his lack of feeling.  

878
01:29:36,720 --> 01:29:40,640
She would have liked Charles to beat her so 
that she could have a reason for hating him.  

879
01:29:41,360 --> 01:29:46,080
She was torn between a love she could not 
admit to, and a hatred she could not show.  

880
01:29:47,200 --> 01:29:54,640
And there she sat at the end of another empty 
day, broken, motionless, her face wet with tears.

881
01:29:56,560 --> 01:30:01,200
'Why don't you tell the doctor about it?' said 
her maid when she came in and found her like this.

882
01:30:02,960 --> 01:30:08,640
'It's only nerves,' answered Emma. 'Don't 
mention it to him. He would only worry.'

883
01:30:11,360 --> 01:30:15,840
If Emma was unhappy, Leon was also 
less than pleased with his life,  

884
01:30:16,480 --> 01:30:22,080
feeling he had nothing to look forward to. He 
was so tired of Yonville and its inhabitants  

885
01:30:22,080 --> 01:30:25,440
that the sight of certain people 
and certain houses made him angry.  

886
01:30:26,560 --> 01:30:32,800
And when Monsieur Homais, the pharmacist, tried to 
amuse him, he found himself disliking him too. The  

887
01:30:32,800 --> 01:30:38,240
problem was, however, that the thought of changing 
things alarmed him as much as it excited him.

888
01:30:39,440 --> 01:30:42,640
And the more he thought about it 
all, the more impatient he became.  

889
01:30:43,760 --> 01:30:49,040
'Paris' was the word he kept saying to 
himself. Since he had to go there for his final  

890
01:30:49,040 --> 01:30:55,600
examinations, why not go now? What was stopping 
him? And he began to plan a new life for himself.  

891
01:30:56,160 --> 01:31:01,600
He would live like an artist. He would take 
guitar lessons. He would wear a red coat  

892
01:31:01,600 --> 01:31:06,560
and a blue hat; he would go to the opera 
every night and drink wine with actresses!  

893
01:31:07,680 --> 01:31:12,560
The great difficulty would be to persuade 
his mother to agree - but, in fact,  

894
01:31:12,560 --> 01:31:17,920
it was quite easy. His own employer had been 
telling him to take up work in another office  

895
01:31:17,920 --> 01:31:22,880
and widen his experience, and his mother 
wanted Leon to qualify as soon as possible.  

896
01:31:23,840 --> 01:31:29,840
Two days after he had sent his letter, she 
wrote back to him giving her permission!

897
01:31:30,480 --> 01:31:36,240
When he knew he could leave, however, he 
did not hurry. Every day, for a whole month,  

898
01:31:36,800 --> 01:31:41,760
boxes and parcels were delivered to his 
rooms in Yonville; and although Leon had  

899
01:31:41,760 --> 01:31:46,400
soon made enough preparations - and more 
than enough - for a voyage round the world,  

900
01:31:47,200 --> 01:31:49,600
he kept putting things off from week to week.

901
01:31:51,120 --> 01:31:57,680
However, at last the time came to leave, and he 
hardly had time to say goodbye to Monsieur Bovary.  

902
01:31:57,680 --> 01:32:02,960
He ran up the stairs to the sitting room, 
and as he went in Madame Bovary rose quickly.

903
01:32:04,560 --> 01:32:06,240
'Here I am again!' said Leon.

904
01:32:07,600 --> 01:32:08,720
'I knew you would come!'

905
01:32:10,080 --> 01:32:15,200
She bit her lip hard, and could feel herself 
blush from the roots of her hair to the edge  

906
01:32:15,200 --> 01:32:19,440
of her collar. She remained standing, 
leaning her shoulder against the wall.

907
01:32:21,120 --> 01:32:22,880
'Is the doctor in?' he said.

908
01:32:24,480 --> 01:32:28,640
'No, he's gone out.' And she 
repeated, 'He's gone out.'

909
01:32:29,680 --> 01:32:30,880
Then there was silence.

910
01:32:32,000 --> 01:32:34,640
'I would like to kiss Berthe goodbye,' he said.

911
01:32:35,920 --> 01:32:39,840
Emma went down a few stairs and called Felicite.

912
01:32:40,480 --> 01:32:44,160
He gave a long look round - 
at the walls, the shelves,  

913
01:32:44,160 --> 01:32:47,600
the fireplace - as if to carry 
the memory of it away with him.

914
01:32:48,960 --> 01:32:54,800
Emma returned, and the servant came in with 
Berthe. Leon kissed her several times on the neck.

915
01:32:55,840 --> 01:32:59,680
'Goodbye, my poor little thing; 
goodbye, my darling, goodbye.'  

916
01:33:00,640 --> 01:33:02,080
And he gave her back to her mother.

917
01:33:03,760 --> 01:33:05,280
'Take her away,' she said.

918
01:33:06,640 --> 01:33:07,840
And now they were alone.

919
01:33:09,600 --> 01:33:13,840
Madame Bovary had her back to him, her 
face against the glass of the window.  

920
01:33:14,880 --> 01:33:18,800
Leon was holding his cap in his hand 
and beating it gently against his thigh.

921
01:33:20,480 --> 01:33:22,560
'It's going to rain,' said Emma.

922
01:33:23,840 --> 01:33:25,760
'I've got a coat,' he answered.

923
01:33:27,840 --> 01:33:28,160
'Ah!'

924
01:33:29,600 --> 01:33:31,520
She turned away again, her face down.  

925
01:33:33,040 --> 01:33:35,840
No one could have said what Emma 
was looking at through the glass.

926
01:33:38,080 --> 01:33:41,120
'Well, this is goodbye!' he sighed.

927
01:33:42,400 --> 01:33:44,400
She raised her head with a sudden movement.

928
01:33:45,600 --> 01:33:50,320
'Yes, goodbye... Oh, go!'

929
01:33:50,320 --> 01:33:54,880
They advanced towards each other. 
He held out his hand. She hesitated.  

930
01:33:56,080 --> 01:34:01,600
'In the English style, then!' she said, 
putting hers in his, forcing herself to laugh.

931
01:34:03,040 --> 01:34:08,480
Leon felt her hand between his fingers, and 
it seemed that his whole life flowed into it.

932
01:34:09,760 --> 01:34:17,840
Then he released her hand, their eyes 
met for a moment, and he was gone.
 
 
 

933
